# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/blue-listed] The concept of a Blue List was derived in 1971 by Robert Arbib from the National Audubon Society in his article, "Announcing-- The Blue List: an 'early warning' system for birds".
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/blue-listed] The article stated that the list was made up for species that appear to be locally common in North America, but is undergoing non-cyclic declines.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/blue-listed] Starting from 1971, it was utilized to list vulnerable bird species throughout North America.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/blue-listed] Unlike the US Fish and Wildlife Endangered Species List, the Blue List was made to identify **patterns** of population losses for regional bird populations before they could be listed as endangered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/blue-listed] Every decade after its release, the list is revisited and revised based on regional editors and species get "nominated" to be added to the list.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/blue-listed] Using this metric reginal editors were able to report on the species along with their status ranks in order to identify the patterns of population growth that each species is facing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] The **Committee on the Status of Endangered Wildlife in Canada** (**COSEWIC**, French: **Comité sur la situation des espèces en péril au Canada**, **COSEPAC**) is an independent committee of wildlife experts and scientists whose "raison d'être is to identify species at risk" in Canada.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] It designates the conservation status of wild species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] It was established in 1977 to provide a single, scientifically sound classification of wildlife species at risk of extinction.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] In the 2002 Species at Risk Act, COSEWIC was appointed as the body to identify and assess a species status.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] Although the status assigned by COSEWIC is not legally binding, it does report its results to the government and the public.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] The report is influential toward the addition of species to the List of Wildlife Species at Risk by the Minister of the Environment.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] By December 2013 there were "686 wildlife species in various COSEWIC risk categories, including 196 Special Concern (SC), 166 Threatened (T), 302 Endangered (E), 22 Extirpated (XT) (i.e., no longer found in the wild in Canada) and 15 wildlife species that are Extinct (X).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] The other category is not at risk (NAR).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] COSEWIC provides online updated status reports on designated species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] COSEWIC bases its quantitative criteria for species' status assessment on the revised IUCN Red List, the world's most comprehensive inventory of the global conservation status of biological species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] COSEWIC provides International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), the world's main authority on the conservation status of species, with a Regional Red List.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] The **conservation status** of a group of organisms (for example, a species) indicates whether the group still exists and how likely it is to become extinct in the near future.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] Many factors are taken into account when assessing conservation status—not simply the number of individuals remaining, but the overall increase or decrease in the population over time, breeding success rates, and known threats.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] Various systems of conservation status are in use at international, multi-country, national and local levels, as well as for consumer use such as sustainable seafood advisory lists and certification.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] The two international systems are by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) and The Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species by the International Union for Conservation of Nature is the best known worldwide conservation status listing and ranking system.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] Species are classified by the IUCN Red List into nine groups set through criteria such as rate of decline, population size, area of geographic distribution, and degree of population and distribution fragmentation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] Also included are species that have gone extinct since 1500 CE.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] When discussing the IUCN Red List, the official term "threatened" is a grouping of three categories: critically endangered, endangered, and vulnerable.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] The Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES) went into force in 1975.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] It aims to ensure that international trade in specimens of wild animals and plants does not threaten their survival.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] Many countries require CITES permits when importing plants and animals listed on CITES.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In the European Union (EU), the Birds Directive and Habitats Directive are the legal instruments which evaluate the conservation status within the EU of species and habitats.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] NatureServe conservation status focuses on Latin America, the United States, Canada, and the Caribbean.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] It has been developed by scientists from NatureServe, The Nature Conservancy, and a network of natural heritage programs and data centers.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] It is increasingly integrated with the IUCN Red List system.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] Its categories for species include: *presumed extinct* (GX), *possibly extinct* (GH), *critically imperiled* (G1), *imperiled* (G2), *vulnerable* (G3), *apparently secure* (G4), and *secure* (G5).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] The system also allows ambiguous or uncertain ranks including *inexact numeric ranks* (e.g.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] G2G3) for when the exact rank is uncertain.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] NatureServe adds a qualifier for *captive or cultivated only* (C), which has a similar meaning to the IUCN Red List *extinct in the wild* (EW) status.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] The Red Data Book of the Russian Federation is used within the Russian Federation, and also accepted in parts of Africa.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In Australia, the *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* (EPBC Act) describes lists of threatened species, ecological communities and threatening processes.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] The categories resemble those of the 1994 IUCN Red List Categories & Criteria (version 2.3).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] Prior to the EPBC Act, a simpler classification system was used by the *Endangered Species Protection Act 1992*.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] Some state and territory governments also have their own systems for conservation status.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] The codes for the Western Australian conservation system are given at Declared Rare and Priority Flora List (abbreviated to DECF when using in a taxobox).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In Belgium, the Flemish Research Institute for Nature and Forest publishes an online set of more than 150 nature indicators in Dutch.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In Canada, the Committee on the Status of Endangered Wildlife in Canada (COSEWIC) is a group of experts that assesses and designates which wild species are in some danger of disappearing from Canada.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] Under the Species at Risk Act (SARA), it is up to the federal government, which is politically accountable, to legally protect species assessed by COSEWIC.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In China, the State, provinces and some counties have determined their key protected wildlife species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In Finland, many species are protected under the Nature Conservation Act, and through the EU Habitats Directive and EU Birds Directive.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In Germany, the Federal Agency for Nature Conservation publishes "red lists of endangered species".
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] India has the Wild Life Protection Act, 1972, Amended 2003 and the Biological Diversity Act, 2002.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In Japan, the Ministry of Environment publishes a Threatened Wildlife of Japan Red Data Book.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In the Netherlands, the Dutch Ministry of Agriculture, Nature and Food Quality publishes a list of threatened species, and conservation is enforced by the Nature Conservation Act 1998.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] Species are also protected through the Wild Birds and Habitats Directives.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In New Zealand, the Department of Conservation publishes the New Zealand Threat Classification System lists.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] As of January 2008 threatened species or subspecies are assigned one of seven categories: Nationally Critical, Nationally Endangered, Nationally Vulnerable, Declining, Recovering, Relict, or Naturally Uncommon.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] While the classification looks only at a national level, many species are unique to New Zealand, and species which are secure overseas are noted as such.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In Russia, the Red Data Book of the Russian Federation came out in 2001, it contains categories defining preservation status for different species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In it there are 8 taxa of amphibians, 21 taxa of reptiles, 128 taxa of birds, and 74 taxa of mammals, in total 231.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] There are also more than 30 regional red books, for example the red book of the Altaic region which came out in 1994.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In South Africa, the South African National Biodiversity Institute, established under the National Environmental Management: Biodiversity Act, 2004, is responsible for drawing up lists of affected species, and monitoring compliance with CITES decisions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] It is envisaged that previously diverse Red lists would be more easily kept current, both technically and financially.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In Thailand, the Wild Animal Reservation and Protection Act of BE 2535 defines fifteen reserved animal species and two classes of protected species, of which hunting, breeding, possession, and trade are prohibited or restricted by law.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] The National Park, Wildlife and Plant Conservation Department of the Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment is responsible for the regulation of these activities.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In Ukraine, the Ministry of Environment Protection maintains list of endangered species (divided into seven categories from "0" - extinct to "VI" - rehabilitated) and publishes it in the Red Book of Ukraine.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] In the United States of America, the Endangered Species Act of 1973 created the Endangered Species List.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] The categories do not simply reflect the imperilment of individual species, but also consider the environmental impacts of how and where they are fished, such as through bycatch or ocean bottom trawlers.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] Often groups of species are assessed rather than individual species (e.g. squid, prawns).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/conservation-status] The Marine Conservation Society has five levels of ratings for seafood species, as displayed on their *FishOnline* website.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The federal government is constitutionally mandated for the conservation and protection of fisheries resources in all Canadian fisheries waters.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] However, the department is largely focused on the conservation and allotment of harvests of salt water fisheries on the Atlantic, Pacific and Arctic coasts of Canada.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The department works toward the conservation and protection of inland freshwater fisheries, such as on the Great Lakes and Lake Winnipeg, through cooperative agreements with various provinces.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Provincial governments have enacted provincial fisheries legislation for the licensing of their fisheries.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] With the exception of Saskatchewan, conservation rules for freshwater fisheries are enacted under the *Fisheries Act*; six provinces administer these regulations in their own fisheries.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] To address the need for conservation, the department has an extensive science branch, with research institutes across the country.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Typically the science branch provides evidence of the need for conservation of various species, which are then regulated by the department.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] DFO also maintains a large enforcement branch with peace officers (known as fishery officers) used to combat poaching and foreign overfishing within Canada's Exclusive Economic Zone.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] DFO is responsible for several organizations, including the Freshwater Fish Marketing Corporation and the Canadian Hydrographic Service.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The Department of Marine and Fisheries was created on July 1, 1867, although it did not receive legislative authority until May 22, 1868.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The department's political representative in Parliament was the minister of marine and fisheries, with the first minister having been Peter Mitchell.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The department was headquartered in the Centre Block of Parliament Hill until the fire of 1916, after which it was moved into the West Block and then off Parliament Hill entirely when new government office buildings were constructed in Ottawa.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] DFO is organized into seven administrative regions which collectively cover all provinces and territories of Canada.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Responsibility for the construction and operation of canals was given to the department of public works at the time of confederation, with the canals of the United Province of Canada having been previously operated by that colony's department of public works.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] In its early days, one of the department's most active agencies was the operation of the Marine Service of Canada, which became the forerunner to the Canadian Coast Guard, with vessels dedicated to performing maintenance of buoys and lighthouses.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Whereas fisheries management was not as important as it became in the latter part of the 20th century, a major responsibility for the Department of Marine and Fisheries included the provisioning of rescue stations and facilities at the shipwreck sites of Sable Island and St.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The department also had responsibility for overseeing the qualification of apprenticing sailors who desired to become mates or shipping masters, as well as several marine police forces, which attempted to combat illegal crimping, the trafficking of sailors in human bondage at major ports.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The foray into enforcement saw the department operate the "Dominion cruisers" which were armed enforcement vessels operating for the Fisheries Protection Service of Canada, a continuation of the Provincial Marine enforcement agencies of the British North American colonies.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] These ships and other chartered schooners and the like, would cruise the fishing grounds off the Atlantic and Pacific coasts, watching for violations within Canada's territorial sea, then only three nautical miles (6 km) from shore.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Prior to the First World War, Canada had limited naval forces, with the majority of protection having been provided by the enforcement vessels of the Department of Marine and Fisheries (Dominion Cruisers) or Fisheries Protection Service of Canada, and by Britain's Royal Navy.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] In 1909–1910, the Department of Marine and Fisheries became linked to efforts to develop a Canadian naval force, when on March 29, 1909, a member of parliament, George Foster, introduced a resolution in the House of Commons calling for the establishment of a "Canadian Naval Service".
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The resolution was not successful; however, on January 12, 1910, the government of Prime Minister Sir Wilfrid Laurier took Foster's resolution and introduced it as the Naval Service Bill.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] After a third reading, the bill received royal assent on May 4, 1910, and became the *Naval Service Act*, administered by the minister of marine and fisheries at the time.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The Naval Service of Canada changed its name to "Royal Canadian Navy" on January 30, 1911, but it was not until August 29, 1911, that the use of "*Royal* Canadian Navy" was permitted by King George V.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The Conservation & Protection (C&P) directorate is responsible for fisheries enforcement.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The program aims to ensure the conservation and sustainable use of Canada's aquatic resources and the protection of species at risk, fish habitat, and oceans.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] C&P collaborates with a variety of domestic partners, including the Canadian Coast Guard, other federal departments, other levels of government, industry, First Nations communities, recreational fishing groups, and others.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Internationally, C&P participates in or indirectly contributes to more than a dozen regional fisheries management organizations (e.g., Northwest Atlantic Fisheries Organization and the North Pacific Anadromous Fish Commission).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The program includes operational enforcement units in DFO's six regions, the National Fisheries Intelligence Service, the National Digital Forensics Service and Program and Operational Readiness.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Enforcement activities are conducted by three types of officials that are designated under the *Fisheries Act*: fishery officers, fishery guardians, and fishery inspectors.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Fishery officers are designated under section 5(1) of the act and defined as peace officers under the *Criminal Code* with the authority to enforce all provisions of the act and other related acts (e.g., the *Coastal Fisheries Protection Act*) and their regulations.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] There are currently more than 600 fishery officers serving in more than 100 detachments and offices across Canada.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] DFO's chief fishery officer is the Director General, Conservation & Protection; as of April 2019, the incumbent is Darren Goetze.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Fishery guardians are also designated under section 5(1) of the act and as peace officers but are not necessarily employed by the department.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] For example, a provincial conservation officer may be designated as a fishery guardian for the purpose of enforcing the act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] In general, fishery guardians cannot conduct a search unless authorized by a warrant or conditions are met under the warrantless search provisions of the *Criminal Code*.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Under the Aboriginal Guardian Program, certain First Nations may submit to the minister to designate certain band members as guardians.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] In October 2017, DFO and the National Indigenous Fisheries Institute (NIFI) launched a full and collaborative review of the department's indigenous programs, including the Aboriginal Guardian Program.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Fishery inspectors are designated under section 38(1) of the act, specifically to enforce the pollution prevention sections of the *Fisheries Act*.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] They are not peace officers and have limited powers *vis-à-vis* the other two designations.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The directorate uses the Smith & Wesson Model 5946 as the standard sidearm.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Since confederation, the responsibilities of the original Department of Marine and Fisheries, namely the Fisheries Service and the Marine Service, have transferred to several other departments.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] The legal name of the department is the Department of Fisheries and Oceans.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] It is also referred to as "Fisheries and Oceans Canada" under the Federal Identity Program.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/department-of-fisheries-and-oceans] Text of each law and its regulations can be found by entering the name of the law at the Canadian Legal Information Institute website.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] A **distinct population segment** (**DPS**) is the smallest division of a taxonomic species permitted to be protected under the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] *Species*, as defined in the Act for listing purposes, is a taxonomic species or subspecies of plant or animal, or in the case of vertebrate species, a distinct population segment.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] Three elements are considered in a decision regarding the status of a possible DPS as endangered or threatened under the Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] The population segment's conservation *status* in relation to the Act's standards for listing (i.e., is the population segment, when treated as if it were a species, endangered or threatened?).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] It is delimited by international governmental boundaries within which differences in control of exploitation, management of habitat, conservation status, or regulatory mechanisms exist that are significant in light of section 4(a)(1)(D) of the Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] In carrying out this examination, the Services [USFWS and NMFS] will consider available scientific evidence of the discrete population segment's importance to the taxon to which it belongs.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] Evidence that the discrete population segment differs markedly from other populations of the species in its genetic characteristics.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] Because precise circumstances are likely to vary considerably from case to case, it is not possible to describe prospectively all the classes of information that might bear on the biological and ecological importance of a discrete population segment.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] If a population segment is discrete and significant (i.e., it is a distinct population segment) its evaluation for endangered or threatened status will be based on the Act's definitions of those terms and a review of the factors enumerated in section 4(a)of the Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] It may be appropriate to assign different classifications to different DPSes of the same vertebrate taxon.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] The Fish and Wildlife Service's Listing and Recovery Priority Guidelines (48 FR 43098; September 21, 1983) generally afford DPSes the same consideration as subspecies, but when a subspecies and a DPS have the same numerical priority, the subspecies receives higher priority for listing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] The Services will continue to generally accord subspecies higher priority than DPSes.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] In consideration of Pacific salmon for listing under the Act, NMFS has relied on the evolutionarily significant unit (ESU) concept and previous developed a policy on the definition of species under the Act (56 FR 58612– 58618; November 20, 1991).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] The policy applies only to species of salmonids native to the Pacific.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] Under this policy, a stock of Pacific salmon is considered a DPS if it represents an evolutionarily significant unit (ESU) of a biological species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] A stock must satisfy two criteria to be considered an ESU: (1) It must be substantially reproductively isolated from other conspecific population units; and (2) It must represent an important component in the evolutionary legacy of the species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] The 1996 joint policy considers the 1991 NMFS policy on Pacific salmon to be consistent with the joint policy, being a detailed extension of it.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/distinct-population-segment] The joint policy further states that NMFS will continue to exercise the 1991 policy with respect to Pacific salmonids.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The **EAZA Ex-situ Programme (EEP)** is a population management and conservation programme by European Association of Zoos and Aquaria (EAZA) for wild animals living in captivity in European zoos and aquaria.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The programme was formerly known as the European Endangered Species Programme.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Each EEP has a coordinator who is assisted by a species committee.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Together with the EAZA Species Committee, recommendations are made each year about relocating and breeding animals, and the conditions of such a move (breeding loan, exchange, term free disposition, etc.).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Even though EEP participation is mainly reserved for EAZA zoos, it is possible for non-EAZA collections to be included in these programmes.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] There are generally however more restrictions on such zoos (which may go as far as only holding non-breeding animals for educational purposes), and on the number of programmes they may participate in.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] For zoo visitors to have the opportunity to see how wild animals look, live, and behave, zoos must ensure that truly wild animals, with all of their natural characteristics, are presented.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Zoo animals are vulnerable to three very serious breeding problems inherent to small, artificial populations: inbreeding depression, loss of genetic variability, and accumulation of deleterious mutations.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] These problems can easily result in loss of original wild traits, and in the expression of heritable abnormalities.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] If what was once a pure, wild population of animals deteriorates through generations of uncontrolled breeding into inferior or partially domesticated stock, then the animals are no longer suitable for any conservation effort, and the zoos have failed to perform an important educational task.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The effects of breeding captive populations of wild animals over periods of many generations have been well studied.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Based on these studies and genetic theory, guidelines for breeding such small populations have been developed.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Following such guidelines should sharply reduce possibilities of breeding problems and concurrently should maximize the number of generations in which the original founding diversity can be maintained.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The application of these guidelines, and many others tailored to specific populations, results in strictly controlled breeding programmes in which nothing is left to chance.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Only in this manner can healthy and truly wild populations be maintained over a period of one or two hundred years.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Such strict control is entirely dependent on cooperation among zoos that hold individuals of the species, as single zoos generally do not have the facilities to maintain a population of adequate size independently.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] As of 2022, over 400 animal species are represented in the EAZA Ex-situ Programme.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] One species which has been handled by EEP was Sumatran tiger which have only a few hundred left in the wild, and only about 7% of their habitat remains.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] They used to live in all the Sumatran territory, but nowadays most of them can only be found in the mountain regions of the Burit Barisan volcanic area.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] This species is currently threatened with the destruction of habitat and poaching, for trade of its parts in traditional oriental medicine or as a trophy.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The Tiger EEP has made contributions to the conservation of Amur and Sumatran tigers in the wild, via fundraising for wild tiger conservation projects, raising awareness and providing educational opportunities, and assisting with relevant research and training.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] For example, in November 2011, Sumatran tiger Kirana has delivered three cubs at Chester Zoo under EEP which attempts to coordinate breeding between zoos and maintain genetic diversity.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The Gorilla EEP is one of the most intensively managed and oldest breeding programmes in European zoos.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The Gorilla EEP was started in 1987 and was run by the Frankfurt Zoological Garden, who continue to maintain the Gorilla Studbook.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] In the past decade, some major improvements have been achieved in the management of the EEP for the western lowland gorilla *Gorilla gorilla gorilla*.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Neonatal mortality and hand‐rearing rates have decreased; transfers in most cases proved to be successful: almost all gorillas were integrated into their new groups and most animals introduced to a breeding group had their first offspring within two years.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The results show that the current management approach is successful, and that the population is sustainable and has good genetic health.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Just the incongruencies in laws can sometimes make exchange of specimens for breeding purposes by two closely situated zoos a formidable task if a border happens to lie between them.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Yet successes have been achieved: the growth of the EEP has been considerable since its initiation in 1985.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] EAZA has more than 400 member institutions in 47 countries throughout Europe, Western Asia and beyond.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] EAZA currently manages EEPs for over 500 different species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] More than 300 EAZA members were participating in EEP programmes in 2021.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] EEP is one of the worldwide assembly of such regional breeding programs in zoos for threatened species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The North America counterpart is the Species Survival Plan, and Australian, Japanese, Indian, and Chinese zoos also have similar programs.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Combined, there are now many hundred zoos worldwide involved in regional breeding programs.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The Endangered Species Act (ESA) was first passed in 1973 and forms the basis of biodiversity and endangered species protection in the United States.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The original purpose of the Endangered Species Act of 1973 was to prevent species endangerment and extinction due to the human impact on natural ecosystems.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The three most powerful sections of the ESA are Sections 4, 7 and 9.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Section 4 allows the Secretaries of Interior and Commerce to list species as threatened or endangered based on best available data.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Section 7 requires federal agencies to consult with Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS) or National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS) before taking any action that may threaten a listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Section 9 forbids the taking of an endangered species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The first amendment to the ESA was passed by the 95th United States Congress in 1978 to "introduce some flexibility into the Endangered Species Act".
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The snail darter case was an important test case of the ESA because it made Congress realize how powerful the ESA really was.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In 1966, the Tennessee Valley Authority began construction on the Tellico Dam on the Little Tennessee River.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] For years, environmentalists tried to shut down the project, but their actions were unsuccessful until the discovery of the snail darter, a small fish that feeds off aquatic snails.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The snail darter was listed as an endangered species in 1975 and part of the Little Tennessee River was designated as critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The completion of the Tellico Dam threatened the survival of the snail darter, which was thought to be native only to the Little Tennessee River.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In 1976, battle in the courts between the Tennessee Valley Authority and environmentalists began over the fate of the snail darter.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Over the next three years, the decision was appealed all the way to the Supreme Court.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Supreme Court ruled in favor of protecting the species "whatever the cost".
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The Endangered Species Act was clear in stating that no federal project should be exempt from the provisions of Section 7.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Starting in the spring of 1977, members of Congress made several attempts to pass legislation that weakened the ESA.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Many large business interest groups, including the mining and timber industries, also spoke out against the power of the ESA.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Beginning in April 1978, the Senate Subcommittee on Resources Protection began debating and developing a bill that would create a committee with power to exempt federal actions from Section 7 requirements.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] On April 12, 1978 Senator John Culver (D-IA) and Senate Minority Leader Howard Baker (R-TN) introduced a bill that would create a seven-member Cabinet-level committee with the authority to exempt a federal agency from Section 7 requirements.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Meanwhile, in Wheatland, Wyoming, a consortium of energy utilities were attempting to build the Grayrocks Dam on the Laramie River to supply a coal-fired power plant.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Upset that water diversion would threaten the critically endangered whooping crane, on October 2, 1978, the Nebraska Attorney General’s office obtained a federal injunction barring the dam.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Grayrocks, however, enjoyed strong support in Congress, and by October 14 Teno Roncalio (D-WY) convinced the House to pass a bill exempting the dam from all federal regulation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In lieu of that, Senator Culver (D-IA) adapted the bill to his own attempts to exempt the snail darter, creating the Endangered Species Committee and required the committee to decide on an exemption from protections of the snail darter and the whooping crane within 30 days.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Both the House of Representatives and Senate voted to amend the ESA, and on November 10 President Jimmy Carter signed the amendment into law.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] On December 4, Nebraska reached a settlement under which the power utilities would get to build Grayrocks dam by agreeing to purchase some habitat for the whooping crane.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] On January 23, 1979, the Endangered Species Committee met for the first time, refused to exempt the snail darter from protection, and granted Grayrocks an exemption from the whooping crane protections.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The most important change that was brought about by the 1978 amendment was the creation of the Endangered Species Committee, known as the "God Squad" because of the substantial impact of its decisions on the natural world.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] One or more temporary members, sharing a single vote, may also be appointed by the President to represent any states that are affected by the exemption in question.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] This committee has the authority to exempt a project or action from Section 7 requirements, which otherwise prohibit actions that are "likely to jeopardize the continued existence" of a listed species or its habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] To exempt an action, at least five members must vote in favor of the exemption.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] 4. neither the federal agency or the exemption applicant made irreversible commitment to the resources.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Additionally, mitigation efforts must be taken to reduce the negative effects on the endangered species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The amendments also contain provisions for the Secretary of Defense or the President to authorize exemptions, in cases of national security or disaster situations respectively.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Conversely, the Secretary of State may overrule exemptions if they are found to violate any international treaties.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In 1991, a federal judge ordered the halting of logging on Pacific Northwest national lands because of the threat to the northern spotted owl.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Following this action, the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) filed for exemption from Section 7.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The northern spotted owl is a medium-sized bird that is dependent on old-growth forest and large territories for survival.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The BLM came up with a solution that allowed logging to continue in the area, which included the sale of timber on 44 timber tracts to the logging industry.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The 44 tracts totaled 4400 acres (18 km2) of land.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The God Squad convened and discussed the issue.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In a 5:2 vote, the God Squad voted for approval of the exemption in thirteen of the sales where there was no reasonable alternative to the sale.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] However, the exemption was soon overturned when Judge Stephen Reinhardt on the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals found it had been illegal for the President to talk to his cabinet about the exemption.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The environmentalists and the BLM agreed on a compromise that allowed the timber sale to continue.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The BLM would develop a Long Range Forest Management Plan that would need to be approved by the FWS before any future timber sales.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] When the Clinton administration came into office, they withdrew the exemption request and convened a conference resulting in appointment of the Forest Ecosystem Management Assessment Team (FEMAT).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The FEMAT was created to develop a plan to protect the owl while still maintaining logging and forest management across the region.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] FEMAT and the Clinton administration agreed to protect 10 million acres (40,000 km2) of old growth forest for the owl, while limiting logging to 1 billion board feet (2,400,000 m3) per year.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] On March 31, 2026, a meeting of the God Squad voted to exempt oil and gas mining companies operating in the Gulf of Mexico from the Endangered Species Act, on unspecified national security grounds.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The decision was requested by US Secretary of Defense Pete Hegseth.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] A similar announcement earlier in the month resulted in a lawsuit that adequate public notice was not provided.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Environmental advocates were concerned the decision could cause the extinction of Rice's whale, which only lives in the Gulf of Mexico and is critically endangered after population loss caused by the Deepwater Horizon oil spill.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] This decision overrides mitigation measures such as slowing down boats in whale habitat, keeping a safe distance from whales, and using quieter air guns for seismic surveys.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The **Endangered Species Act of 1973** (**ESA**; 16 U.S.C. § 1531 et seq.) is the primary law in the United States for protecting and conserving imperiled species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Designed to protect critically imperiled species from extinction as a "consequence of economic growth and development untempered by adequate concern and conservation", the ESA was signed into law by President Richard Nixon on December 28, 1973.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Supreme Court described it as "the most comprehensive legislation for the preservation of endangered species enacted by any nation".
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The purposes of the ESA are two-fold: to prevent extinction and to recover species to the point where the law's protections are not needed.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It therefore "protect[s] species and the ecosystems upon which they depend" through different mechanisms.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] For example, section 4 requires the agencies overseeing the ESA to designate imperiled species as threatened or endangered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Section 9 prohibits unlawful 'take,' of such species, which means to "harass, harm, hunt..." Section 7 directs federal agencies to use their authorities to help conserve listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The ESA also serves as the enacting legislation to carry out the provisions outlined in The Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Act is administered by two federal agencies, the United States Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS) and the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] FWS and NMFS have been delegated by the Act with the authority to promulgate any rules and guidelines within the Code of Federal Regulations to implement its provisions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Calls for wildlife conservation in the United States increased in the early 1900s because of the visible decline of several species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] One example was the near-extinction of the bison, which used to number in the tens of millions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Similarly, the extinction of the passenger pigeon, which numbered in the billions, caused concern.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The whooping crane also received widespread attention as unregulated hunting and habitat loss contributed to a steady decline in its population.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] By 1890, it had disappeared from its primary breeding range in the north central United States.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Scientists of the day played a prominent role in raising public awareness about the losses.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] For example, George Bird Grinnell highlighted bison decline by writing articles in *Forest and Stream*.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] To address these concerns, Congress enacted the Lacey Act of 1900.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Lacey Act was the first federal law that regulated commercial animal markets.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It also prohibited the sale of illegally killed animals between states (interstate commerce).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Other legislation followed, including the Migratory Bird Conservation Act, a 1937 treaty prohibiting the hunting of right and gray whales, and the Bald and Golden Eagle Protection Act of 1940.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Despite these treaties and protections, many populations still continued to decline.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] By 1941, only an estimated 16 whooping cranes remained in the wild.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] By 1963, the bald eagle, the national symbol of the U.S., was in danger of extinction in the lower 48 states.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Only around 487 nesting pairs remained outside of Alaska.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Loss of habitat, shooting, and DDT poisoning contributed to its decline.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Fish and Wildlife Service tried to prevent the extinction of these species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Yet, it lacked the necessary Congressional authority and funding.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] In response to this need, Congress passed the Endangered Species Preservation Act (Pub.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Act initiated a program to conserve, protect, and restore select species of native fish and wildlife.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] As a part of this program, Congress authorized the Secretary of the Interior to acquire land or interests in land that would further the conservation of these species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Department of Interior issued the first list of endangered species in March 1967.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It included 14 mammals, 36 birds, 6 reptiles, 6 amphibians, and 22 fish.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] A few notable species listed in 1967 were the grizzly bear, American alligator, Florida manatee, and bald eagle.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Endangered Species Preservation Act was repealed by the Endangered Species Act of 1973.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Endangered Species Conservation Act of 1969 (Pub.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] 91–135) amended the Endangered Species Preservation Act of 1966.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It established a list of species in danger of worldwide extinction.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It also expanded protections for species covered in 1966 and added to the list of protected species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] While the 1966 Act only applied to 'game' and wild birds, the 1969 Act also protected mollusks and crustaceans.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Punishments for poaching or unlawful importation or sale of these species were also increased.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Any violation could result in a $10,000 fine or up to one year of jail time.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Notably, the Act called for an international convention or treaty to conserve endangered species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] A 1963 IUCN resolution called for a similar international convention.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] In February 1973 a meeting in Washington, D.C. was convened.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] This meeting produced the comprehensive multilateral treaty known as CITES, or the Convention on International Trade of Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Endangered Species Conservation Act of 1969 provided a template for the Endangered Species Act of 1973 by using the term "based on the best scientific and commercial data." This standard is used as a guideline to determine if a species is in danger of extinction.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] In 1972, President Nixon declared current species conservation efforts to be inadequate.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] He called on the 93rd United States Congress to pass comprehensive endangered species legislation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Congress responded with a completely rewritten law, the Endangered Species Act of 1973, which was signed by Nixon on December 28, 1973 (Pub.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It was written by a team of lawyers and scientists, including Russell E.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Train, the first appointed head of the Council on Environmental Quality (CEQ), an outgrowth of the National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA) of 1969.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Train was assisted by a core group of staffers, including Earl Baysinger at EPA, Dick Gutting, and Gerard A.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] "We didn't know what we couldn't do", Bertrand has said about the Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Significant amendments to the Act happened only four times during the first half-century of the Act's implementation: 1978, 1982, 1988, and 2004.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] These are listed and summarized on a U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Fish and Wildlife Service webpage titled, "History of the Endangered Species Act: Principal Amendments".
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] How the official regulations for implementing the Act have developed and changed through time is more complex and is not available on the agency website.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Endangered Species Act is administered by two federal agencies, the United States Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS) and the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] NMFS handles most marine species, and the FWS has responsibility over freshwater fish and all other species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Species that occur in both habitats (e.g. sea turtles and Atlantic sturgeon) are jointly managed.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The 1973 Act is considered a landmark conservation law.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Formal regulations published in the *Federal Register* that specify how the Act will be implemented have also changed through time.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] In recent years, U.S. presidential elections that greatly shift environmental priorities have culminated in regulatory shifts in endangered species management back and forth.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Congressional elections also affect implementation of the Act via expansions or contractions in annual funding decisions for the agencies.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] A distinction of the 1973 Act is that, unlike the previous legislation, plants became eligible for listing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Fifty years later, significantly more species of plants were listed in the highest category (endangered) than animals: 766 plants and 486 animals.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The agency maintains a webpage that lists all the endangered and threatened plant species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Almost all listings are at the species level, but a few are subspecies or varieties.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Historians attribute this new-found concern for imperiled plants to ongoing global treaty negotiations (especially in 1972 and 1973) toward what would eventually be adopted in 1975 under the title, Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Prior to this time, attention to the conservation needs of native plants had been stalled by complications that do not pertain to animals.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] How to adequately distinguish plants illegally collected in the wild from plants propagated from seeds or cuttings taken from horticultural specimens was among the points of contention.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Ultimately, federal authority over enforcement of endangered plant protections has centered on regulation of interstate commerce of such plants.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Because movement of seeds and seedlings by this group was noncommercial and based on horticulturally produced specimens, there was no legal apparatus to halt their actions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Another distinction is that, when an animal is listed as endangered, "taking" of that animal (by capture or killing) becomes a violation of the Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] For plants, "taking" occurs only within the boundaries of federal properties.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Even so, states may choose to legislate and enforce prohibitions even on private lands, as occurred in 2023 when the State of California passed a law that prevented killing or removal of the western variety of Joshua tree wherever it was found.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Climate change risk was a key factor in the determination.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Act distinguished two grades of species for listing: "**endangered**" and a lesser category called "**threatened**".
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The agency maintains a webpage that lists all the endangered and threatened animal species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The set is organized into ten groups and appears on the webpage in this order: amphibians, arachnids, birds, clams, crustaceans, fishes, insects, mammals, reptiles, and snails.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The agency maintains a webpage for the public to access the complete **list of endangered animals** and a separate webpage for **endangered plants**.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The agency also maintains a webpage that lists in tabular format all the species of plants and animals that have been "**reclassified**" and when that occurred.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Total entries on that list were 65 as of February 2025.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Some entries are just populations rather than full species or subspecies.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] For example, at the beginning of the list are two populations of California tiger salamander; one is in Sonoma County and the other in Santa Barbara County.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Both were reclassified from endangered to threatened in August 2004.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] There is also an online webpage that documents in tabular format all species that have been "**delisted**." One of the columns is used to distinguish whether the species is foreign or domestic.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] A key provision of the 1973 Act was that "preventing extinction" would no longer be sufficient.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Rather, "recovery" of listed species, such that "delisting" could ensue, became a stated goal.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The complications and controversies arising during recovery plan development and approval have meant that the two-year deadline for producing a plan after a new species is listed have sometimes met with long delays.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The 1973 Act introduced the concept of what is now called "critical habitat" in only one brief passage.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The 1978 amendments also provided for the consideration of economic impacts when designating critical habitat, and provided a mechanism for excluding critical habitat where the benefits of exclusion would outweigh the benefits of designating the area as critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] As will be seen in the "Controversies" section, this provision is sometimes challenging to implement for both scientific and political reasons, as when more than a million acres of critical habitat was proposed in 2024 for the rusty patched bumblebee and officially adopted in 2026.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] As of June 2026, 995 critical habitat documents pertaining to all species are listed and linked online by the agency.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Act, as amended, directs all federal agencies to use their authorities to help conserve listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Documents that are published in advance of action decisions include environmental impact statements and formal biological opinions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Those that pertain to lands that include critical habitat designations provide the grounds for developing site-specific restrictions or requirements for mitigating impacts on listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] As of April 2026, the **Biological Opinions** webpage lists 4,736 entries.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Some of those biological opinions and reports aggregate a number of species into a single document to support interagency cooperation and the development or updating of official recovery plans.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The central feature of the Act is listing, protecting, and recovering domestic species of animals and plants that are threatened or endangered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Additionally, Section 8 of the Act directs that international treaties and conventions pertaining to imperiled species are also to be implemented.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The same year that the U.S. endangered species legislation was being shaped, an international effort to enact something similar was underway.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The **Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora**, abbreviated as CITES, is a multilateral treaty to protect the plants and animals that are largely imperiled by international trade.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It was drafted as a result of a resolution adopted in 1963 at a meeting of members of the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The convention was opened for signature in 1973 and CITES entered into force in July 1975.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] As of 2025, roughly 6,610 species of animals and 34,310 species of plants are protected internationally against over-exploitation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] In 1992, the Supreme Court ruled that citizens do not have standing to sue the federal government for providing funds to other countries for uses that may harm foreign species that are listed as endangered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] As of 2023, those deadlines still nominally apply, but in practice it is rare for a petitioner to approach the judicial system to force a decision before the agency is able to finish the job on its own timetable.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The Endangered Species Act of 1973 (ESA) is regarded as "one of the most powerful and controversial environmental laws in the United States." In 2023, with the Act achieving its 50th anniversary, journalists were prompted to report on the Act's outcomes and controversies.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Congressional overturning of several recent listings and ability to hamper implementation by restricting agency funding were among the points mentioned by some media.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] An academic review paper in 2008 reported that the Act had become "a social, legal, and political battleground" and that "the scientific question of whether the ESA works effectively to protect species remains open." Indeed, endless litigation has become a defining feature of ESA implementation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Specific challenges and long-term controversies are summarized in this multi-part section.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Support for learning and evaluating the history of ESA implementation is an online system maintained by the federal government whereby a great variety of reports published during the five decades of endangered species implementation can be accessed.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The numbers and complexity of those documents are the focus of the fourth topical section included below.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] For now, the list shown here is just one section of the gateway webpage for accessing reports by species, by region, and by other factors.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] "**ECOS: Environmental Conservation Online System**" is the name of the governmental website, and the gateway page is **ECOS Species Reports**.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] All the decisions and reports and supplementary materials pertaining to implementation of the Act are posted by the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Fish and Wildlife Service through that system.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Because some of the challenges and controversies arising from implementation of the federal Act entail interactions with various state governmental priorities and programs, it is important to establish the background of state jurisdiction.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] For example, downlisting of the Chiricahua leopard frog from endangered to threatened is attributed to state-level efforts by Arizona and New Mexico.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The need for a federal listing of the Mardon skipper butterfly was avoided, owing to cooperative early efforts by the states of Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In practice through the decades, the federal-state relationship has not always been congenial.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Elected officials at both federal and state levels sometimes escalate calls for outright devolving endangered species management to the states.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] An overall federal policy for collaboration, however, is not achievable because the kinds and scale of species-protective laws, regulations, and implementation priorities vary enormously among the states.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As well, only California and Oregon authorize citizens to petition for state-level listings, and distinctions prevail in matters concerning critical habitat designations and the degree to which species protections can impinge on land use choices by private owners.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Nothing prevents a state from issuing stricter regulations for a federal listed species within its boundaries.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A 2018 survey of state laws found that Illinois, Massachusetts, and Wisconsin "even go beyond the ESA in their protective measures." As well, nothing prevents a state from listing a species that the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Fish and Wildlife Service formally decides against.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] An example of federal-state tensions occurred in California in July 2023.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It was then that California enacted its own "Western Joshua Tree Conservation Act." This halted all sales of the western species of *Yucca brevifolia*, while instituting a permit process for any proposed removal, harm, or trimming of the species on private lands.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The legislature itself chose to pass this law after the federal agency had formally decided against listing on two occasions: August 2019 and March 2023.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The second decision had been forced by a 2021 court remand of the 2019 decision, and was based on a "Species Status Assessment Report" (173 pages) that had been published by the agency the prior month.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] An important distinction of California's 2023 Joshua Tree statute is that it did not confer even state-level listing of this plant as threatened or endangered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Instead, a highly collaborative "**Western Joshua Tree Conservation Plan**" would be established and implemented (the draft was published December 2024).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This would pre-empt the need for California's state-level Fish and Game Commission to decide upon an already pending listing petition in accordance with the California Endangered Species Act (CESA).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Despite the State of California's initiative, a national environmental organization (WildEarth Guardians), went to the federal court system again.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In May 2025, the court ruled in their behalf.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In October 2025, the State of California once again took actions to supersede federal ESA implementation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] That same month, the California Department of Fish and Wildlife euthanized four federally endangered wolves that had recently established in a cattle ranching part of the state.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The petitioning, listing, and recovery planning stages prescribed in the Act have a history not only of contentiousness but of delays and setbacks owing to all three branches of the federal government sometimes becoming involved.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This is especially the case when a federal listing would apply to an animal whose widely dispersed populations are declining over a vast landscape.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Potential listing of the Lesser prairie-chicken is one such example.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 1995 the Center for Biological Diversity, along with other conservation groups, petitioned for listing the lesser prairie-chicken.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Agency recognition of the bird as a "candidate species" in 1998 deferred formal review while the agency worked its way through a backlog of previous petitions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In an effort to achieve habitat improvement agreements with state and private landowners prior to (and possibly thereby precluding) a listing decision, a "voluntary prelisting conservation program" was launched in 2010 — not by the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Department of Interior (which includes the Fish and Wildlife Service), but by the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This government-led project was unusual for an at-risk species in that it was launched with the expressed intent to promote the long-term sustainability of ranching operations while improving the population and occupied territory of the lesser prairie-chicken.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Conservation groups were keen on collaborative agreements not only for the wellbeing of this grassland bird but because of its ecological role as an umbrella species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Protecting the habitat needs of an umbrella species thereby also protects the habitat of dozens of other at-risk species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] That project did not advance well enough to preclude a listing petition in 2012, which resulted in a formal listing as "threatened" in 2014.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This action was overturned by the courts in 2015, when it was challenged by business interests associated with oil and gas extraction.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Conservation groups resumed petitioning for listing of the species, with the executive branch repeatedly deferring a decision until 2022.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It was then that a listing was finalized that classified the southern population as endangered and the northern population as threatened.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] However, in 2023 Congress passed a bill that negated the listing, which was promptly vetoed by President Biden.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 2025, a federal court in Texas ruled in favor of a case filed by the State of Texas and several petroleum companies that pointed to problems in the 2022 listing decision.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The Trump Administration did not defend against the lawsuit and even requested the court to overturn the listing rule.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In sum, from 1998 to early 2026, two executive agencies of the federal government, two judicial actions, and one attempt by Congress to overturn a listing decision all played roles in how the Endangered Species Act would be applied to the conservation of the Lesser prairie-chicken.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] An even more complicated example is the gray wolf, as presented in a 2020 report by the Congressional Research Service subtitled, "A Case Study in Listing and Delisting Challenges." Details of this report appear in a delisting section later on this page.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The ESA, as amended, specifies the use of science in two distinct areas of decision-making.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] First, determinations whether to list (and downlist or delist) species must be made "solely" on the basis of science, without consideration of how a listing decision might adversely affect other national or regional priorities.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Second, all agency decisions on managing species that are already listed must be made using "the best available science." Together, these two mandates have generated considerable discord and lawsuits on a variety of agency decisions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] To begin, the statute requires that agency decisions on listings must not be influenced by political, corporate, or citizen concerns that such listings could impinge on access to natural resources on public lands or how private landowners choose to manage their own properties.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Rather, listings are to be based "solely" on the science.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] But even peer-reviewed science publications can be at odds, thus offering grounds for opposing parties to each present rational arguments that their position is more in line with the science than that of their opponents.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Additional points of contention arise when "the best available science" is clearly deficient.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In these circumstances even the Information Quality Act guidelines issued by the federal Office of Management and Budget, along with the scientific integrity policies of the implementing agencies, may offer little support for resolving debates and thus preventing lawsuits.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] If staff time is already overwhelmed by existing legal requirements for decision-making and if the budget lacks capacity for hiring research by contractors, decisions will have to be made despite even large unknowns in the data and conclusions of science.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Parties who strongly disagree with the agency decision may then utilize the Administrative Procedure Act to contest the outcome in court, if they can construct a good case that established agency norms for decision-making were violated.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Overturn of the Chevron deference by the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Supreme Court in 2024 may have amplified opportunities for judicial scrutiny of agency decisions to the point that even "the best available science" aspects can be argued in court.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Among the most polarizing provisions in the Act are the rights awarded to citizens (and their interest groups) to compel the agency to make listing decisions, to specify "critical habitat", and then to challenge in court such decisions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] To begin, citizens are authorized to submit petitions proposing the listing of new species and to have those petitions officially responded to in accordance with deadlines set forth in the Act, as amended.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Decisions to list (or not to list), along with the degree of protection granted (endangered or threatened), are then vulnerable to citizen litigation in federal courts.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In practice, agency decisions are sometimes challenged by biodiversity proponents who assert that "the best available science" would compel stronger listing protections.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Decisions are also sometimes challenged by oppositional interest groups, notably by those grounded in business, extractive industry, or landowner rights perspectives.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A review article published in 2025 on lessons learned from implementation of the ESA reports on how the "best available science" understandings have evolved through time, including examples (notably, population viability analysis) where experts continue to disagree.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Supreme Court in 2024 may have amplified opportunities for citizens pro and con to obtain judicial scrutiny of agency decisions grounded in arguable "best available science" and the unavoidably ambiguous standards written into the statute.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Citizen suits are not unique to the Endangered Species Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A 2004 paper reported that "sixteen of the nation's principal federal environmental laws invite citizens to sue" to force agencies to perform mandatory duties.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Disagreement amplified when some environmental interest groups began submitting mega-petitions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 2011 a "mega-settlement" was achieved by the agency, WildEarth Guardians, and another biodiversity advocate group, Center for Biological Diversity.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The settlement required FWS to take action on pending petitions for 757 species over the next seven years.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In exchange, the two environmental groups agreed to limit lawsuits filed against the agency so that efforts could be focused on trying to accomplish the terms of the agreement.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The following year, however, the Center for Biological Diversity submitted a single petition for listing a total of 53 amphibians and reptiles spanning a range of 45 states.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The list of citizen petitioners included two well-known ecological scientists: Edward O.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] From a practical standpoint, citizen suits are unlikely to be launched frivolously because of the costs of attorney time, coupled with the need to obtain a win in order to benefit from court-ordered reimbursement of legal expenses.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] United States Fish and Wildlife Service*, Edward Poitevent and his family have owned land in St.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Tammany Parish, Louisiana, since the end of the Civil War.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The family relies on this land for their livelihood, having signed a 90-year lease in the 1950s to preserve their property.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In the 1990s, the Weyerhaeuser Company acquired this lease for timber operations.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 2012, the USFWS designated over 1,500 acres of Poitevent's property as critical habitat for the dusky gopher frog, a species that had not been sighted in Louisiana for 50 years.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The nearest population of this frog was located nearly 70 miles away in Mississippi, leading many to argue that the designation was an arbitrary bureaucratic decision that restricted Poitevent's property rights and froze an estimated $34 million in economic activity.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Supreme court affirming that the Fish and Wildlife Service exceeded its statutory authority in making the critical habitat designation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Marina Point Development Corp.*, the plaintiffs filed citizen suit actions under the Clean Water Act (CWA) and the Endangered Species Act (ESA) against a developer, claiming violations by the construction project.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] After the district court ruled in favor of the plaintiffs, the developer appealed.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] On appeal, the court found that the plaintiffs had not met the 60-day notice requirement for their CWA claims and that the ESA claims were moot due to the delisting of the bald eagle in 2007.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As a result, the appellate court ordered the vacatur of both the district court's judgment and its opinion.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Bernhardt*, Ken Klemm managed a 4,000-acre bison ranch for over two decades, focusing on bison grazing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Fish and Wildlife Service regulations that treated species at minimal extinction risk similarly to those facing imminent danger.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 2019, the Department of Interior reformed the Endangered Species Act (ESA), reinstating a two-step protection system to alleviate burdens on landowners like Klemm.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A lawsuit from 17 states and environmental groups challenged these reforms, leading Klemm to intervene.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] On July 5, 2022, a district court vacated the 2019 reforms without evaluating their legality.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The Ninth Circuit subsequently ruled that federal regulations cannot be rescinded without judicial review, allowing the 2019 rules to remain while the agency undergoes a formal amendment process.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Citizens (including non-governmental organizations) are empowered to petition a species (or distinct population of a vertebrate species) to be designated as threatened or endangered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Decision documents (first in draft, then in final) are posted in the Federal Register.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Draft decisions are to be posted for comment within two years, but in practice it often takes the agency much longer.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Because the statute directs the agency to use "the best available science" when evaluating a petition, no new scientific research needs to be conducted before issuing a response.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Even so, staff time and resources may be substantial, partly to ensure that the resulting decision derives from a document that can allay disappointed stakeholders from going to court.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Decisions on petitions have been most challenged when the Center for Biological Diversity or WildEarth Guardians submit "mega-petitions" that request decisions on scores of species at the same time.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Failure to meet the regulatory deadlines could subject the agency to judicial review.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Only Congress can forestall those kinds of lawsuits.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Thus, in 2011 the Fish and Wildlife Service itself requested Congress to impose a cap on the portion of the agency's budget that could be spent responding to petitions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A **recovery plan** (with or without critical habitat designations) is the major document prepared by the agency following a listing decision of threatened or endangered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Reviews of the plan, with updates if merited, are to be performed every five years.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The statutory requirement for other federal agencies to act in ways supportive of listed species is generally referred to as "**agency consultation**." This is where the decision-making, documentation, and public participation becomes more complex.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The Congressional Research Service (CRS) produced (and periodically updates) a detailed online document whose purpose is to make the Act and its implementation outcomes understandable to members and staff of the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Titled, "The Endangered Species Act: Overview and Implementation," the document has lengthy sections pertaining to the complexities of and distinctions between **Section 7 "Interagency Consultation"** and **Section 10 "Exceptions"**.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Legally required written documents that result are known as "**Incidental Take Statements**" (ITS), which is an outcome of Section 7 of the Act, and two documents arising from Section 10: **Incidental Take Permits** (ITP) and **Habitat Conservation Plans** (HCP).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A two-page version of just the "Section 7 Consultation" process, requirements, and document outcomes was published by the CRS in 2023.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In it, one learns distinctions between a "**biological assessment**" and a "**biological opinion**" (BiOp).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The latter may contain an "incidental take statement" (ITS) if an endangered species could experience "jeopardy" if the action moves forward.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Environmental Impact Statements (EIS) and subsequent permitting actions are administered by the Environmental Protection Agency, with requirements for consulting with the Fish and Wildlife Service within specified time parameters.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The same holds for actions and permitting authorities of the Bureau of Land Management, Forest Service, and Army Corps of Engineers.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Entities seeking development permits on federal lands may be required to develop "**Habitat Conservation Plans**" (HCP) that may include mitigation efforts, monitoring, and even supporting additional field science.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] HCP documents can be accessed individually by the development project title through the ECOS portal.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] For example, the "Criterion Wind Power" project has an individual page.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Its permit to proceed was issued in 2014 for a duration of 21 years.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Subsidiary links include two versions of the HCP, two Biological Opinions, a NEPA-EA, a NEPA-FONSI, and a "Set of Findings".
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Finally, although not subject to public comment requirements via draft publication in the *Federal Register*, the Fish and Wildlife Service has been making the recovery plan stage less complex by creating policy-free and science-rich "**Species Status Assessments**" (SSA).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] These are posted on a dedicated ECOS portal, with summary statements later embedded into the formal, and policy-rich recovery plan documents.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Controversy sometimes roils when the timing of a petition to list a new species overlaps with plans for or initiation of a development project that could be impeded by such a listing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A news editorial marking the 50th anniversary of the Act suggested that "the ESA became the weapon of choice for environmental groups seeking to stop projects or tear down others.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Lawsuits by the score have been filed over projects large and small, setting off ill feelings toward environmental groups." A prominent example of this dynamic was the listing of the coastal California gnatcatcher.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Some observers opined that the impetus for listing was in part borne out of the species being considered a "flagship" for the coastal sage scrub ecosystem of southern California—an area subject to significant pressure for housing development.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Because the Act allowed species to be listed as endangered without consideration of the economic consequences, it soon became and continues to be controversial.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Costs conferred on private landowners and various industries may come in the form of lost opportunity or slowing down operations to comply with the regulations put forth in the Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Notably, in 1978 the listing of a tiny fish (snail darter) shut down for several years construction of a dam that was already underway on the Little Tennessee River.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] More broadly, the requirement to consult with the relevant agencies on federal projects has at times slowed operations by the oil and gas industry, including exploration or development on federal lands rich in fossil fuels.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Due to political backlash stemming from the snail darter decision, in 1978 Congress amended the ESA to be more sensitive to costs.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The 1978 amendments also amended the **Section 7 consultation process** to authorize FWS and NMFS to allow projects that may affect listed species or habitat to continue if there are "reasonable and prudent alternatives" that minimize adverse impacts.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] These amendments to the critical habitat and Section 7 consultation processes (along with additional amendments made in 1982) were designed to offset the consequences of the cost-neutral process for the initial listing of species, and to improve flexibility in the ESA's application.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Notwithstanding the 1978 and 1982 amendments, one widely held opinion remains that the protections afforded to listed species curtail economic activity.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In the extreme, economic consequences can induce perverse incentives by which landowners actively curtail their lands from attracting endangered species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] An example in the eastern USA pertains to the endangered red-cockaded woodpecker.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A 1995 study of some 1,000 privately owned forest plots within the range of the woodpecker found that when landowners observed pine growth maturing to a stage in which it might attract nesting woodpeckers, they were more likely to harvest – regardless of timber prices at the time.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This is a form of intentional habitat destruction for avoiding economic consequences.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] By 2024, however, recovery actions had gone well enough for the federal agency to downlist the species from endangered to threatened.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Downlisting was achieved in large part because of a linked pair of innovative conservation documents negotiated between landowners and the federal agency: **Conservation Benefit Agreement (CBA)** and **Enhancement of Survival (EOS)** permit.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Legislators have expressed that the ESA has been "weaponized," particularly against western states, constraining state government choices about the use of public lands.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The case of the protracted dispute over the greater sage-grouse is one such example, and the spotted owl is another.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In the extreme is the largely western saying pertaining to endangered animals, such as wolves: "shoot, shovel, and shut up." Rep.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Some economists have stated that finding a way to reduce such perverse incentives would lead to more effective protection of endangered species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] One suggestion for ending perverse incentives would be to compensate property owners for protecting endangered species, rather than having an endangered species regarded as a potential financial loss.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] 4. would give landowners a reason to maintain their property in species-friendly condition.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As well, while the standard to prevent jeopardy or adverse modification, under Section 7 of the ESA, applies only to federal activities (which can, however, include private activities that require a federal permit), entirely non-federal activities are subject to Section 10 of the Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] To work toward conservation solutions before perverse incentives develop, the "Conservation Without Conflict" initiative and coalition was formed in 2017, with guidance presented in a series of eight steps.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Other collaborations supported by nongovernmental organizations focus on ranching and forestry stewardship initiatives.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The Supreme Court ruling in *Tennessee Valley Authority v.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Ever since the Supreme Court ruling in the snail darter case, interest groups with a biocentric focus have had strong grounding for challenging agency listing decisions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Another consequence of the snail darter ruling is that formal listing decisions sometimes include lengthy expositions of scientific details.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This way, it is clear that the "best available science" has indeed been consulted.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A highly controversial, and thus lengthy, listing decision was issued in 2022.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It pertains to a small flowering plant in the desert of southwest Nevada.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The published document in the *Federal Register* that establishes Tiehm's buckwheat as an endangered species is 33 pages long, inclusive of a "critical habitat" designation for 910 acres that was simultaneously issued.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Six of the total pages are responses to each of 29 comments elicited when the required draft of the listing was published.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The foundational document that established the "best available science" for making the listing decision was previously published as a "**Species Status Assessment**", which in itself was 80 pages long in PDF format.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A recent example of competing priorities happened when the federal government was compelled to make a listing decision on a petition.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 2019 the Center for Biological Diversity petitioned to have a small flowering plant in Nevada listed as endangered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A mining project by Ioneer, an Australian company, was already preparing the site for extracting lithium and boron.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Environmental interests were thus divided between those focused on species protection and those advocating for electric vehicles, which require lithium as the key component of the lightest-weight batteries.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] While economic concerns and priorities are restricted from playing a role in governmental listing decisions, the 1978 amendments to the Act did make it possible for these matters to impinge on the designation of critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Because the endangered listing decision and critical habitat specification occurred in the same document in 2022, this resulted in something unusual: Both the Center for Biological Diversity (CBD) and the mining company posted support for the decision.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] CBD was enthusiastic about the endangered listing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Ioneer already had developed a plan to begin mining that would not interfere with the 910 acres of critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In this case, the critical habitat and its surrounds were entirely on public lands managed by the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It thus fell to that agency, in consultation with the Fish and Wildlife Service, to make the final decisions about whether, where, and how the mine could proceed.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The Bureau granted approval October 2024.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Numerous associated documents can be found on the agency's webpage for the Rhyolite Ridge Project, with all the underlying reports and documents fulfilling the requirements of the National Environmental Policy Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The approval was preceded by a 2023 "Public Scoping Report" that was 15 pages, plus more than 100 pages of appendices.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Ioneer also has a publicly accessible website, where it publishes all the documents preceding and related to the permit decision.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] One of the links goes to "Ioneer's Buckwheat Protection Plan Summary: Proposed Conservation Measures for Tiehm's Buckwheat and Critical Habitat." Another page on the website describes the company's past and future conservation efforts.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The 50th anniversary of the ESA was in December 2023.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As the time approached, interest groups and journalists began writing about the results of its implementation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As of August that year, an aggregate of 1,780 species had been cumulatively listed as "**endangered**" or a lesser category of "**threatened**".
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] While 99% of the total species were still alive, critics pointed out that only 64 species had improved enough to be declared as **recovered** and thus removed from the list (**delisted**).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A data point on the positive side was that a different set of 64 species had improved enough to be **downlisted** from endangered to threatened.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Among the most celebrated successes is that of the American alligator.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This reptile was listed as endangered in 1967.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Twenty years later it was delisted as fully recovered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] However, because of its resemblance to its endangered saltwater relative in Florida, the American crocodile, hunting and commercial trade regulations have been maintained for this species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The most controversial measure of effectiveness, however, pertained to the published number of cumulatively listed species that had gone **extinct**.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As the autumn of 2023 began, the official number was 11.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] But another 23 species had gone missing for so long that in September 2021 the agency had published a 41-page draft ruling in the *Federal Register* to officially declare those 23 species extinct.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It took two years for the agency to finalize its proposed ruling, but in October 2023 the controversy was settled.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The agency ruled as extinct 21 of the 23 species it had proposed.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Declared extinct were Bachman's warbler, which had been native to Florida and South Carolina, along with nine tropical birds (8 in Hawaii and 1 in Guam).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Hope still remained for one bird, the Ivory-billed woodpecker.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The only other species that remained listed as endangered was a Hawaiian plant in the mint family.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Another controversy has been ongoing for more than three decades.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Some have argued that the recovery of imperiled flesh-eating birds (notably, the bald eagle, brown pelican, and peregrine falcon) should be attributed to the 1972 ban of the pesticide DDT by the EPA, rather than the Endangered Species Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Supporters of the Act argue that listing these species as endangered led to additional actions that were also crucial for species recovery (i.e., captive breeding, habitat protection, and protection from disturbance).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Among the most difficult species to protect are mussels because they depend on adequate amounts of clean and flowing freshwater.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Home to approximately 300 mussel species, the eastern region of the USA is the center of global diversity for these freshwater molluscs.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] However, 65 percent of them are threatened or endangered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The 1988 Congressional amendments to the Act included a new section, Section 18, to aid effectiveness evaluations by having each of the two implementing agencies periodically report cumulative federal funding (and, to some degree, state funding) on a species-by-species basis.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As of 2026, the agency webpage titled "Endangered and Threatened Species Expenditures Reports" lists and links annual reports from fiscal year 1989 through 2020, but for no later years.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The above section on "effectiveness" of the Act is examined here as to why it is that recovery, and thus delistings, are rare.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A widely used statistic supporting effectiveness of the Act is that 99 percent of listed species have not gone extinct.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Full recovery may thus be slow, but substantial progress is evidenced when a species is **downlisted** from endangered to threatened.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] For example, National Marine Fisheries Service lists eight species (or populations of a species) as among the most at risk of extinction in the near future.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] These animals are the Atlantic salmon; the Central California Coast coho salmon; the Cook Inlet beluga whale; the Hawaiian monk seal; the Pacific leatherback sea turtle; the Sacramento River winter-run chinook salmon; the southern resident population of killer whale; and the white abalone.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Human activities are presented as the primary cause of extinction threats for all these species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] While the two implementing agencies have a combined record of changing species status from threatened to endangered on nine occasions, the number of status improvements from endangered to threatened is greater.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] On the opposing side of the spectrum, a foundation associated with the Western Caucus of U.S. senators and representatives issued a 116-page report in 2023 that points to data and statements made by the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Fish and Wildlife Service during the past half-century that can be interpreted as disputing proclamations of success.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Specifically, statements of numbers of species "recovered" do not distinguish between those delisted owing to actual improvement in populations versus those for which the original population numbers were later found to have been greatly underestimated.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Had the science been more in line with reality at the start, this report claims 36 of the 62 species reported by the agency as officially recovered would not have achieved listing at the outset.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Controversy also develops when the science used to support a delisting decision differs from the numerical population thresholds included in the **species recovery plan**.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] For example, the listing of the California sea otter has been controversial with fishermen who contend that the sea otter's expansion from Monterey into Southern California waters has resulted in a dramatic reduction in sea urchin, abalone, and other commercially valuable species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] These impacts led certain fishermen groups to petition the government to delist the sea otter.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The petition argued that delisting is appropriate because, among other reasons, the sea otter's population goals, as contained in the most recent recovery plan, have been met.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The government, however, denied the petition.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A 2012 court case upheld the agency decision, ruling that published recovery criteria are not legally binding for later delisting decisions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Accordingly, during the early 2020s an even more controversial agency response against a delisting petition was supported by that court decision.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It pertained to the grizzly bear in six distinct populations.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 2024 a "new metric to evaluate recovery progress" was published by 13 coauthors.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Listing of a species "triggers two overlapping types of conservation measures: extinction prevention and recovery actions." An official document required by the Act has come to be known as a recovery plan.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Besides alleged funding inadequacies, several inherent problems have been pointed to for delays in agency translation of scientific findings into actions beyond extinction prevention and thus actively toward species recovery.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] One such problem is the "knowledge—action boundary" that distinguishes conservation scientists from conservation managers.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] That is, how can scientific scholarship be made actionable, and thereby contribute directly to forward-moving policies and practices?
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] "Fear of failure in conservation" is another factor that contributes to agency and manager hesitancy to undertake recovery actions for which there is no certainty of success.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] There are two reasons why scientists themselves may abstain from recommending actions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] One is fear that making such recommendations may compromise their status as objective researchers whose conclusions can be trusted.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A second is fear that a recommended action that is undertaken but then fails may injure their reputation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] These fears may be heightened when recommendations pertain to a species for which controversy has developed or one whose population has declined so drastically that any manipulation of the species or its habitat may later be denounced as contributing to its further decline or extinction.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Species recovery is slowed by inherent complexities.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Fish & Wildlife Service maintains a webpage that sets forth the **stages of the recovery process**.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Fish and Wildlife Service itself has recognized that specifying in a written plan the actions to achieve recovery goals falls short of ensuring that such actions will take place.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Statutory and regulatory requirements for producing an initial **recovery plan** are still fulfilled, including opportunities for public comments.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The plan is to be written and published in the customary way, and it continues to be subject to the "five year review" process.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] However, two new kinds of working documents can be developed, posted, and updated as needed for each listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The first updatable document is a **Species Status Assessment (SSA)**.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It is "a biological risk assessment to aid decision makers who must use the best available scientific information to make policy decisions under the ESA." As new papers are published and rigorous data collected, the SSA can be updated and reposted as warranted.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As of April 2026, 455 listed or petitioned species have had an SSA completed and posted on the FWS aggregate list.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] SSA updates may, in turn, stimulate changes in the third part of the new framework: the **Recovery Implementation Strategy (RIS)**.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Because the agency had been criticized for lacking "clear distinctions between science input and policy application," four FWS agency scientists along with two colleagues in the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Geological Survey published a paper in 2018 in the *Journal of Fish and Wildlife Management*.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Titled, "Development of a Species Status Assessment Process for Decisions under the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] With or without listing, there are opportunities for stakeholders themselves to begin actions on their own.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] This especially applies to habitat improvements.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] If suitable habitat for a species can be found on private, state, municipal, or tribal lands, there is no need to wait for the federal agency to offer or specify in-place actions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The parties can expand and improve such habitats on their own.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] While there are legal limitations on what citizens and other stakeholders can do directly for listed animal species, the field is wide open for obtaining horticulturally produced seeds and specimens of listed plants and then conducting plantings on their own.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A well-known example is a network of citizens who call themselves Torreya Guardians.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Florida Torreya is a glacial relict species of subcanopy tree that was listed as endangered in 1984.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Since 2004, the citizen group has been using seeds from mature plantings on private lands in North Carolina (and since 2018 also from their own plantings in Ohio) to engage in a form of assisted migration poleward of this climate-endangered plant.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Prior to listing of a species, stakeholders who wish to act in its behalf have freedom to engage with not only habitat but with the species itself.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A well-known example entails actions taken in behalf of the subalpine Whitebark Pine of the northern Rocky Mountains soon after vast stands suddenly began to die in Yellowstone National Park and elsewhere.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A petition for listing was submitted in 2008, but status as "threatened" was not conferred until 2022.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] By then, collaboration among concerned parties was well underway without agency direction.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Supportive research and actions were undertaken by the conservation organization American Forests as well as a new organization specific to the tree: the Whitebark Pine Ecosystem Foundation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Other collaborators include research scientists within the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Forest Service, geneticists at the University of California, Davis, and the Confederated Salish and Kootenai Tribes.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Bureau of Land Management and the National Park Service were also involved in consultation prior to listing by the agency in charge of endangered species: the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 188-page **Species Status Assessment** published in 2021 aggregates the scientific information on which the policy decision to list the species as threatened was based.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Controversy is also apparent, though rare, when stakeholders entail activists who regard the "political-economic regime" not as the source of solutions but as "the root cause of biodiversity loss." In such instances guerrilla rewilding of rare species has been known to occur.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The 1982 amendments to Section 10 of the Act authorized collaborative engagement of the implementing agencies with landowners in producing Habitat Conservation Plans.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Such a plan is a required part of an application for an Incidental Take Permit, issued under the Act to private and other nonfederal entities undertaking projects that might result in harm to a listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The intent is to deter controversy by building into the plan practices for minimizing harm to listed species and their core habitat needs (including seasonal peaks in use).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A validated plan then absolves the landowner (or developer) from harms that may incidentally occur to the species, when following the plan.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Securing landowner pledges of habitat enhancement measures during the planning process can serve to defuse opposition from the public and other stakeholders.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Plan preparation is generally initiated and produced by a nonfederal entity: private landowner, state government, local government.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As of 2021, more than 700 habitat conservation plans were in force for listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A leading example is the plan produced by the state of Massachusetts in 2016 to reduce conflicts between a type of beach-nesting shorebird, piping plover, and recreational beach users along the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Such plans also apply to the red-cockaded woodpecker of forests in the southeastern states.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In 2024 a new program went into effect: **Conservation Benefits Agreement** (CBA).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] It combined and streamlined two previous opportunities for landowners to initiate their own conservation projects and thereby obtain assurances that stabilize how federal policies apply to their actions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] An example of a CBA that was approved in 2025 was initiated by a minerals corporation with lands in southeastern Arizona.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The voluntary agreement benefits three endangered fish species (spikedace, loach minnow, and Gila chub) and one threatened snake (narrow-headed garter snake).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The agreement will remain in effect for 50 years.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 2019 report found that the Fish and Wildlife Service faced a backlog of more than 500 species that have been determined to potentially warrant protection.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 2022 report pointed to severe population declines while species await listing decisions as a major problem impeding eventual recovery success.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The decision to list or defer listing of a petitioned species is supposed to take no more than 2 years after a petition is filed.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] However, on average it takes the agency 12 years to finalize a decision.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] An analysis published in 2016 by the Ecological Society of America found that approximately 50 species may have gone extinct while awaiting a listing decision.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Additional funding might enable the agency to direct more resources toward biological assessments of petitioned species and determine if they merit a listing decision.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] An additional issue is that species still listed under the Act may already be extinct.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] For example, the IUCN Red List declared the Scioto madtom extinct in 2013.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] This freshwater species had last been seen alive in its small native range in Ohio in 1957.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] However, it was not until 2023 that the FWS officially declared this catfish as extinct.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As of February 2025, the Fish and Wildlife Service online system that catalogs all current listing proposals that have not yet been processed shows there are 65 outstanding domestic and foreign species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The list aggregates the proposed species into broad taxonomic types.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Counting only the domestic (not the foreign) species on the list, there are: 5 amphibians, 3 birds, 13 freshwater clams, 3 crustaceans (crayfish), 8 fishes, 3 flowering plants, 7 insects, 2 mammals (1 rat and 1 bat), 12 reptiles, and 2 snails.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Bipartisan support for the Endangered Species Act of 1973 began to unravel almost immediately when a tiny fish native to Tennessee, the snail darter, tested the strong biocentric focus of the Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Elsewhere on this page, and also on a distinct wikipedia page, the snail darter controversy is dealt with at length.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Here it is important to mention that in 2025, tools for making taxonomic determinations had advanced to the point that the snail darter is no longer regarded as a species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] From the beginning, implementation of the ESA of 1973 is based on "the best available science," beginning with taxonomic classification.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The petitioned group of organisms must first qualify as a bona fide species or subspecies.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Isolated populations or varieties of otherwise common species may be considered for listing only if they are vertebrates.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Given the evolutionary processes by which species arise and continue to change, there is no consensus that could provide a singular definition or standard for the agency to use.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Classification is therefore determined on a case-by-case basis and generally secured by publication in an academic journal — which itself is vulnerable to publish-or-perish motivations that can lead to what is called taxonomic inflation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] This in itself can make the posting of a listing decision vulnerable to public attack.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Supreme Court in 2024 may have amplified classification as grounds for litigation by opponents of endangered species listings.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] To begin, improvements in conservation genomics established that the already-listed red wolf evolved as a hybrid of native gray wolves and coyotes who interbred in the eastern states.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The problem compounded when the red wolf population managed on a coastal island became populous enough for geographic range experimentation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Individuals released onto the mainland routinely interbred with the far more populous coyotes, and genetic swamping ensued.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Other listed animals embroiled in hybridization controversies include the golden-winged warbler, westslope cutthroat trout, the wood bison, and the eastern massasauga rattlesnake.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] An example for plants in which a taxonomic decision required listing as a distinct species a globe mallow in Arizona concerns the genus *Sphaeralcea*.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Only once has hybridization been an intentional recovery action, known as genetic rescue.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] This was applied to the Florida panther when cougars from Texas were intentionally released into its habitat to counter ongoing decline owing to inbreeding depression.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] This openness to using hybridization to outright save a species contrasted with the agency's decision to deny cross-breeding of the dusky seaside sparrow with its sister species: Scott's seaside sparrow.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 2025 review paper reports that naturally occurring hybridization that is already happening "threatens to swamp" these listed taxa: northern spotted owl, bull trout, California tiger salamander, and red wolf.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Because habitat loss is regarded as the primary threat to most imperiled species, Section 4 of the Endangered Species Act of 1973 allowed the Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS) and National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS) to designate specific areas as protected "Critical Habitat" zones.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The designation of critical habitat does not affect land ownership.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] It does not allow the government to take or manage private property, nor to establish a refuge, reserve, preserve, or other conservation area.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Critical habitat designation does not allow unauthorized government access to private land.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Such designation can, however, severely restrict activities allowable on private lands.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In 1978, Congress amended the law to make critical habitat designation a mandatory requirement for all threatened and endangered species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] To offset some of the consequences of this amendment, and to improve flexibility in the ESA's application, the 1978 amendments also added economics into the process of determining such designation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The controversy did arise and thus the 1982 amendment to the Act explicitly prohibited similar economic considerations when determining the status of a species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In designating critical habitat, the needs of open space for individual and population growth, food, water, light or other nutritional requirements, breeding sites, seed germination and dispersal needs, and lack of disturbances are considered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As itemized within a 2008 review paper on the Endangered Species Act, designation of critical habitat is the first priority for agency action following listing of a species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Not all recovery plans, however, specify critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Most provisions of the ESA revolve around preventing extinction.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Critical habitat is one of the few that focus on recovery.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 2005 paper published in the journal *BioScience* concluded that species afforded critical habitat are twice as likely to be recovering than are species without critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 2016 report published by the Ecological Society of America stated that data were inconclusive on this matter because "in practice, the Services often exempt habitat degradation from regulation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As a result, designating critical habitat has had limited regulatory effect." Overall, disagreement as to the effectiveness of critical habitat designation is expressed in a number of different reports.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Another controversy arises from the Act specifying that critical habitat designation is required to contain "all areas essential to the conservation" of the imperiled species, and may include private as well as public lands.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The Fish and Wildlife Service has a policy limiting designation to lands and waters within the U.S., and both federal agencies may exclude essential areas if they determine that economic or other costs exceed the benefit.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The ESA, however, is mute about how such costs and benefits are to be determined, and USFWS and NMFS have frequently minimized this exclusion provision's application in favor of large critical habitat designations.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] All federal agencies are prohibited from authorizing, funding, or carrying out actions that "destroy or adversely modify" critical habitats (Section 7(a) (2)).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] While the regulatory aspect of critical habitat does not apply directly to private and other non-federal landowners, large-scale development, logging, and mining projects on private and state land typically require one or more federal permits and thus become subject to critical habitat regulations.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Outside or in parallel with regulatory processes, critical habitats also focus and encourage voluntary actions such as land purchases, grant making, restoration, and establishment of reserves.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The Act's specification of the timing of critical habitat designations has also become problematic.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The ESA requires that critical habitat be designated at the time of or within one year of a species being placed on the endangered list.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In practice, most designations occur several years after listing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Between 1978 and 1986, the FWS regularly designated critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In 1986 the Reagan administration issued a regulation limiting the protective status of critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As a result, few critical habitats were designated between 1986 and the late 1990s.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, a series of court orders invalidated the Reagan regulations and forced the FWS and NMFS to designate several hundred critical habitats, especially in Hawaii, California, and other western states.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Midwest and eastern states received less critical habitat, primarily on rivers and coastlines.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As of December 2006, the Reagan regulation had not yet been replaced, though its use had been suspended.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Nonetheless, the agencies have generally changed course.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Since about 2005, both have tried to designate critical habitat at or near the time of listing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The designation of critical habitat has proved to be one of the most controversial aspects of the ESA's administration.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] An example of such controversy can be found in *Weyerhaeuser Company v.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] United States Fish and Wildlife Service.* In this 2018 ruling, the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Supreme Court addressed whether land can be designed as critical habitat even if the land cannot support the existence of protected species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The litigation arose over the designation of loblolly pine timberlands in Louisiana as critical habitat for the dusky gopher frog.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The plaintiffs objected to the designation of their land as critical habitat, citing its significant economic costs, including the inability to develop the land for commercial and residential uses.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Unanimously ruling for the property owners, the Supreme Court held that land cannot be designated as critical habitat if it cannot qualify as habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The dusky gopher frog decision at the level of U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Supreme Court thus became a key species-specific example of the judiciary setting geographic boundaries on the agency's ability to designate critical habitat happened in 2018.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The court ruled as invalid the critical habitat designation of a segment of private timberlands in Louisiana in part because the endangered frog had been extirpated from that state for half a century, currently inhabiting only Mississippi.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Equally, it was clear that suitable pond "habitat" for the frog would require a degree of ecological restoration to be performed on the private land.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 2020 law review article concluded that critical habitat designations were still far underutilized.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In 2005 the Center for Biological Diversity petitioned to list the polar bear as threatened, with critical habitat in Alaska.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Climate change was among the identified threats.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Rising temperatures and declining snowpack in the contiguous United States (not Alaska) had made cave denning difficult for the remaining populations in the Cascade Range and Rocky Mountains.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Because distinct populations of vertebrate species and subspecies can be listed, nine river systems where chinook salmon spawn are now protected under the Act (see image at right).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Salmon spawn in freshwater but mature in marine waters, so both the Fish and Wildlife Service and the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration manage the listing and recovery actions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] While climate change was established in 2008 as a legitimate reason for listing a species, subspecies, or population, climate adaptation became an option for recovery actions only in 2023.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] This was when the geographic scope of the regulation pertaining to "**experimental populations**" was amended.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Although the Endangered Species Act of 1973 (as amended in 1982) did not in itself limit the placement of experimental populations to the "**historical range**" of a plant or animal, a regulatory change in 1984 made prospective translocations beyond the native range more difficult to justify.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Two Congressional Research Service reports focus on experimental populations.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] One summarizes its early use for reasons other than climate change, and the other focuses on its past and present use in helping the gray wolf expand much farther into what had been its vast historical range.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As of February 2025, 64 species (including several populations of a single species) were listed as already having authorizations to implement "experimental populations." All can proceed on a "non-essential" basis (meaning, losses are expected but will not threaten the integrity of the gene pool).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The greatest number of authorizations apply to aquatic species (fishes, clams, mussels).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Two large and charismatic birds have been placed into locales far outside of where their last remnant populations survived prior to listing as endangered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] These are the California condor and the Whooping crane.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Fish and Wildlife Service published a proposed rule in the *Federal Register* that would "revise section 10(j) regulations under the ESA to better facilitate recovery by allowing for the introduction of listed species to suitable habitats outside of their historical ranges.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As reported on the news page of *Audubon*, adoption of the proposed regulatory change would authorize, for the first time, use of a controversial climate adaptation tool: assisted migration.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Department of Interior on June 30, 2023, announced its decision to modify the section 10(j) "experimental populations" rule generally as proposed a year earlier.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The press release summarized the reason for the change as, "At the time the original 10(j) regulations were established, the potential impact of climate change on species and their habitats was not fully realized, yet in the decades since have become even more dramatic.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The rulemaking action includes a section summarizing 25 topics entailed in comments submitted in 2022, along with the agency's official response to each.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Pre-existing requirements pertaining to experimental populations in the Code of Federal Regulations (CFR) still apply.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Plans to use "Subpart H: experimental populations" for the purpose of climate change adaptation thus require public notice and ultimate placement in the "Species-specific rules" subpart of the CFR regulations of the precise geographic and other details.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Six months after this climate adaptation regulation for listed species was published, the National Park Service issued a 154-page report on recommendations for halting the decline of the endangered Karner blue butterfly in its small and scattered populations across the northeastern states.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Among the recommendations were "managed relocation" of populations from the southern parts of its range into northward habitats with suitable conditions and supportive plants.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Two weeks after the 2024 United States presidential election, the founder of a citizen group, Torreya Guardians, urged the new administration to utilize the experimental populations regulation to recruit more citizens to help endangered plants.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The group had been using their own resources to do this for a critically endangered tree since 2008.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Utilizing an exception in the ESA just for plants, they had been experimentally planting **Florida torreya**, *Torreya taxifolia*, hundreds of miles northward of its native range (a glacial refugium) in Florida.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In October 2020, the Gray wolf (but not the Mexican wolf) was delisted by the federal government in all states.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Press releases by the FWS explained the scope and rationale of that action.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Several lawsuits challenging the delisting were filed in the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] District Court for the Northern District of California.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A press release issued by one of the plaintiffs, Defenders of Wildlife, explained, "This decision made wolves vulnerable to hunting, trapping, poisoning, and other lethal controls.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The challenges continued after the report was published.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In February 2022, the district court vacated and remanded the 2020 delisting rule.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] That decision reinstated the federal protections that were in place prior to the effective date of the 2020 delisting rule.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Gray wolves were thus once again listed as threatened in Minnesota and endangered in all or portions of 44 U.S. states and Mexico.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The regional exception where delisting was maintained spanned the 5 states where the Northern Rocky Mountain wolf population had established.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The agency once again went to work on updating the **Species Status Assessment Report**, and creating a formal listing document plus a recovery plan.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] House of Representatives passed a bill to delist the wolf that would override any decision by the agency.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Meanwhile the Nez Perce Tribe has been cooperating with federal authorities in wolf reintroduction on its own tribal lands in Idaho since the 1990s.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The Nez Perce Tribe is not unusual in its respectful relationship to the wolf.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Another large predator species that has been fraught with ESA listing controversy for many years are the populations of grizzly bear outside of Alaska.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The grizzly, too, has a "species status assessment" prepared by the federal government.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Here, too, the Nez Perce Tribe is reported as prohibiting grizzly hunting on tribal lands.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The 398-page federal report does not, however, include any mention of traditional ecological knowledge pertaining to the bear.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The California legislature passed a bill to raise California regulations to thwart the Trump administration changes; it was vetoed by Governor Newsom.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In January 2020, the House Natural Resources Committee reported similar legislation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In December 2020, the Trump administration further rolled back the Endangered Species Act by reducing habitat protections for at-risk species, and thus restricting protections to where they currently live—not where they lived previously or where they might migrate to as a result of climate change.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In June 2021, the Biden administration said it was reviewing the Trump era Endangered Species Act regulations and planned to reverse or revise some of the changes, in particular those relating to critical habitat regulations.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] After a panel of the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals disallowed an initial attempt to immediately reverse these regulations in 2022, the Biden administration embarked on a rulemaking, and a series of less dramatic revisions were finalized in May 2024.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This regulatory flip-flop was not without precedent.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In March 2025 several conservation groups warned that numerous species currently listed could be driven to extinction as a result of the second Trump administration's mass firings of U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A representative of the group Earthjustice was quoted in the article as charging that the committee "can behave as god and decide what species exist and which don't." One year later, March 2026, the cabinet-level committee met for the first time in more than 30 years.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The greater-sage grouse is one declining species for which listing petitions have generated policy responses that flip-flop with presidential (and sometimes Congressional) election results.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Because the bird's sagebrush habitat ranges through ten western states and because much of that habitat is within the jurisdiction of the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Bureau of Land Management, the affected states have advocated for collaborative decision-making as a more malleable alternative to federal designation of the grouse as a threatened species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The first petition was submitted during the George W.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Bush administration, with policy deliberations carrying into President Obama's time in office during which a court order forced a decision on whether or not to list the bird as threatened.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] "Warranted but precluded" was the decision in 2010 that effectively pushed decision-making into an undetermined future time.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In April 2014, the Sage-Grouse and Endangered Species Conservation and Protection Act (H.R.4419) was passed in the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This statute prohibited the federal government from listing sage grouse under the Endangered Species Act for 10 years, so long as states prepared and carried out plans to protect the species within their borders.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A collaborative plan (without formal listing) was finally signed in 2015.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] It carried through the first Trump administration and into the Biden administration.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A few days after the 2024 election results determined that Donald J.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Trump would resume the presidency, the Biden administration offered an updated draft plan.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Many national-level environmental groups communicated support for the plan.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Several, however, pressed for the outgoing administration to formally list the species as threatened, thereby invoking more environmentally stringent decision-making on resource development proposals on federal lands, especially those administered by the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Periodic "reauthorization" by Congress of the ESA of 1973 is a statutory requirement to ensure ongoing appropriations.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The Act was reauthorized for the first time in 1978 during the presidency of Jimmy Carter.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Reauthorization continued in 1982 and 1988 during the presidency of Ronald Reagan.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Four years later another vote for renewal was due, but this did not occur.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] From 1992 on through at least 2024, reauthorization has never again been accomplished.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Mandatory funding for the law therefore expired in 1992.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Even so, partisan compromises that come from the necessity to annually pass an overall federal budget have maintained annual appropriations for continuing enforcement of the Act's provisions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A 2009 law review paper attributed increasing polarization in the "reauthorization debates" partly to the news media having incentives to attract readership by featuring the most dramatic quotations from "divergent narratives" that magnify the divide.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] As well, interest groups on both sides "shared a perception that the ESA was broken." Because any move to reauthorize the Act would also open the prospect for amendment, "legislative gridlock and risk aversion on all political sides" restrain any serious effort to introduce a reauthorization bill.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Opening the Act itself to amendment by Congress has not been achieved in a major way since the amendments of 1988.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In December 2024, a substantial set of amendments was approved by the House Committee on Natural Resources, but nothing of similar scope moved through the Senate.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Nonetheless, Congressional interventions in executive branch implementation are regularly achieved via "riders" inserted into a multi-topic omnibus bill (notably, passage of the annual budget bill).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Very few of these moved out of any committee.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Most were attempts to block funding, overrule listing or delisting decisions, or alter regulations for just one species at a time.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The Fish & Wildlife Service has developed a four-factor prioritization system for analyzing tradeoffs in distributing funds among the listed species: degree of threat, potential for recovery, taxonomic uniqueness, and conflict with human activities.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] As to the implementation of existing recovery plans, there is no requirement that federal agencies (or any other institution) implement any of the actions specified in those plans.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 1988, the 1973 Act was amended in several ways, including the creation of a new section.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The 2020 fiscal year report entailed many pages of tabulations.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] One such list organized the species from the greatest to the least annual expenditures.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Chinook Salmon of Puget Sound was at the top of the list: $62 million.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] All but one of the 26 highest ranked species are fish that live, at least part of their lives, in freshwater habitats.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The one exception is also aquatic, but confined to marine waters and thus administered by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A reptile first shows up on the list as species rank 27.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] It is the desert tortoise, and its recovery actions entailed $8 million in 2020.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Next comes the manatee and soon thereafter the first birds: northern spotted owl and red-cockaded woodpecker.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Those were also in the $8 million range.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The grizzly bear is ranked 46, and it is in the $4 million range.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The first insect, Oregon silverspot butterfly is 139th on the list; its 2020 expenses were $737 thousand.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The American burying beetle is the next insect, at $673 thousand.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Costs escalated for the beetle when "**experimental populations**" were initiated in new locations beginning in 2011.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] One has to scroll down to the 159th highest annual expenditure in order to find the first plant.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] It is a keystone species of coastal waters that provides expansive ecosystem services: seagrass.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Immediately following the seagrass is American crocodile and California condor.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] All three are just under $600 thousand apiece.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] At the opposite end of financial support are species that received the least in 2020.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Of the 1,599 domestic threatened and endangered species ranked in the long series of tables, 668 species were each allocated less than $10,000.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] One plant, one fish, and one snail were in the lowest rank; each was managed with $100.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Cumulative expenditures in fiscal year 2020 for all 1,599 species were also calculated.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This compares to the 2018 fiscal year budget total of $1,269,621,055.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The reporting framework differs from year to year.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 2018, the federal government cost for acquiring lands as critical habitat totaled $105,469,496, of which 45% came from the FWS agency budget and the rest from other federal sources.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Land acquisition expenditures, which may primarily come from the federal Land and Water Conservation Fund, were not included in the 2020 report.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Short reports on **agency requests for FY appropriations and Congressional deliberations thereof** are available for more recent years than the set of lengthy annual reports that documented actual agency expenditures from FY 1989 through 2020.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] For example, there is an online public narrative of the FY 2024 FWS request (with comparisons to 2022 and 2023).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The Congressional Research Service posted a short analysis of same.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] For FY 2024, there is also a lengthy report itemizing costs and requests for more than a dozen programs internal to FWS, but the endangered species program is not delineated among those programs, and there is no species-by-species accounting as had been the norm through 2020.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A notable example happened in 1994 when the eastern North Pacific population of gray whale (which ranges along the west coast of North America) was delisted.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Its population had reached the recovery threshold, and henceforth the Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972 was regarded as sufficient for maintaining that recovery into the future.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This also applied to delisting of the bald eagle in 2007, because DDT had been banned by the Environmental Protection Agency in 1972 and the Bald Eagle Protection Act had made killing of the bird illegal since 1940.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] What about species for whom active management had played a large role in bringing population numbers up to the recovery threshold, yet the threats that had been repelled by such management showed no prospect of going away?
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 2005 these kinds of species were labelled as conservation-reliant species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Accordingly, they would also be funding reliant — but not necessarily dependent on U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Fish and Wildlife funding, nor possibly any other federal agency.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Instead, state agencies and sometimes non-governmental organizations would commit to maintaining the requisite conservation actions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The authors concluded that "the challenge created by the conservation reliance of threatened and endangered species is formidable." This was based on a survey they conducted of the 1,361 existing recovery plans.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Fish and Wildlife Service and the National Marine Fisheries Service had begun using the concept of "conservation reliance" when planning and reporting efforts to recover and delist species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The statutory requirement for ensuring ongoing management by other institutions was achieved by securing management agreements with state governmental and also private entities (such as conservation organizations and conservation land trusts).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] An example well-known for the number of institutions agreeing to bear responsibilities for continuing conservation actions pertains to the 2019 delisting of the Kirtland's warbler.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Designated as "endangered" in 1972 via the 1969 version of the endangered species statute, the warbler had dipped in population as low as 200 breeding pairs.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The initial recovery plan, as required by the 1973 statute, was published in 1976 and set a recovery goal of 1,000 breeding pairs.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] By then the science was clear as to what had been challenging the species for decades.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] One threat was habitat loss and the other was another species of bird.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Habitat loss is attributed to human interventions that severely reduced the scale and repetition of forest fires in the pine-rich ecosystems of northern Michigan.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Kirtland's warblers will nest only in open woodlands dominated by jack pine, and only in the southernmost portion of the tree's otherwise vast range spanning far into Canada.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] But jack pine is an early successional species, and this means that canopy dominants, such as red pine, will eventually shade them out.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] And not just any jack pine can attract these birds to nest.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] There needs to be many of them, scaling to no less than several hundred acres of near monoculture.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Worse, prime habitat is naturally ephemeral.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Kirtland's warblers will nest only on the ground, and thus the protective trees have to be young enough (6 to 20 years old) for the lower branches to fully camouflage their chosen sites.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] But civilization cannot tolerate fires running rampant.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The species of bird that poses an equal threat was native to the prairie states — not the forests of Michigan.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This is the brown-headed cowbird, which had evolved a clever way to raise its young while harvesting insects lofted by roaming herds of bison.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] They had become brood parasites, laying their eggs in the nests of other bird species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] But the bison are gone, and cattle and farm fields have replaced much of the forest in Michigan.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The cowbirds easily adapted to this new landscape, laying their eggs deliberately in the nests of smaller-bodied birds.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Cowbird hatchlings are much bigger than the rightful occupants of the nest, easily pushing them out and also reaching higher to snatch food from the bills of the foster parents.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Active, ongoing management is thus unavoidable.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Controlled burns or jack pine harvests need to be repeated throughout the dedicated and acquired habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] As of 2025, the parties collaborating in these and other efforts are called the Kirtland's Warbler Conservation Team.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] At the time of delisting (2019), team members were drawn from three federal agencies (U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Department of Agriculture), from the state natural resources departments of Michigan and Wisconsin, from the Canadian Wildlife Service, and from two established conservation organizations (The Nature Conservancy and Huron Pines).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Federal expenditures leading up to delisting peaked in 2018, with $432,000 having been expended that year.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] More than half of the budget was attributed to the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Fish and Wildlife Service second, and smaller investments made by the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Geological Survey, the Army Corps of Engineers, and the Department of Agriculture's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] No expenditures were attributed to the Fish and Wildlife Service in 2020, but a total of $27,000 federal dollars were expended by other agencies, mostly the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Forest Service (on whose lands active management continues).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 1978, a small species of fish in the southeastern USA was listed as endangered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A conflict arose because a dam was already under construction within its native range and was scientifically deemed as damaging to its necessary habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] What came to be known as the snail darter controversy gained national attention.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Supreme Court ruling prohibited dam completion, which was then overridden when Congress exempted the Tellico Dam from provisions of the ESA.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Subsequently, more populations of the species were discovered in rivers other than the Little Tennessee River where the dam was constructed, and in 2022 the species was removed from the federal endangered list.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Nonetheless, the fact that the Endangered Species Act effectively halted major construction underway in behalf of a small species of fish put an end to the wide political support that had accompanied passage of the Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 1982, despite protests from some environmental organizations, the recovery plan for the endangered California condor began implementing the capture of all 22 wild birds that remained.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] By the early 1990s, the captive breeding effort was successful enough to begin returning some of the progeny to the wild—including the Grand Canyon from which this carrion-feeding bird had been missing for at least several centuries.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 2001 the first wild nesting was recorded in the Grand Canyon.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] As of 2022, the species had a wild population of 350 individuals and a captive population of 214.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 1987 an extirpated eastern relative of the gray wolf was reintroduced into North Carolina following more than a decade of captive breeding.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Controversy accelerated when the state wildlife agency liberalized hunting regulations for coyotes.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Because the endangered red wolf resembles its coyote relative far more than the larger gray wolf does, the number of mistaken shootings of the endangered species began to seriously impact the population.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] As well, detractors of red wolf protection pointed to the genetic deterioration of later generations of red wolves in the wild, as they easily interbreed with coyotes.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 1988 another controversy arose that drew national attention, when the Northern spotted owl was listed as endangered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This species depended on intact and mature coastal forests in the states of Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] And this, in turn, posed new restrictions on logging of national forest lands in those regions—which devastated local economies in small logging towns across the Pacific northwest.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Not until 1994 did adoption by the federal government of the Northwest Forest Plan, along with a community financial aid packet, bring a close to peak hostilities between loggers and those defending owl habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Preventing human destruction of habitat did not, however, result in species recovery.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Natural immigration of a bigger and more aggressive owl species (the barred owl) that was formerly native only to the eastern states became a major cause of continuing population decline of the spotted owl.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The government's decision to employ sharpshooters to cull the barred owl population presents a challenging ethical issue within conservation thinking.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Another ESA controversy erupted in the 1990s when the gray wolf (listed as endangered in the Lower 48 states in 1974) and the Mexican wolf (listed as endangered in 1976) were reintroduced into core areas of their former native ranges.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Ever after, state authority to manage roaming wolves (and authorize takings and hunts) has been controversial, as well.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Climate change became a legally validated extinction risk when the polar bear secured a listing as "threatened" in 2010.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This was the culmination of five years of contention, beginning in 2005 when the Center for Biological Diversity filed a petition to list the bear as threatened, attributed to data on Arctic sea ice decline already underway.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The Fish and Wildlife Service did not respond to the petition in a timely fashion, resulting in a lawsuit, which in turn prompted an out-of-court settlement that had the agency list the polar bear as threatened in 2008.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This time it was the state of Alaska and industry groups that litigated.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The D.C. district court upheld the listing decision, which prompted the plaintiffs to seek an appeals court ruling.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Again the agency listing decision was upheld, based in part on the reasonableness of the agency using "widely accepted" climate models.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] By 2018, critical habitat designation on private land in Louisiana for the Mississippi gopher frog (also known as dusky gopher frog) had become so controversial that the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Supreme Court chose to adjudicate a lower court decision.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The result effectively removed the habitat designation as overreach, owing to the species having gone missing from Louisiana a half-century earlier.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The agency consequently modified its regulations in accordance with the ruling.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 2022, a 6-inch flowering plant, Tiehm's buckwheat, was listed as endangered and accorded critical habitat protection on 910 acres of federal lands in Nevada.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The listing was controversial because mining for lithium (crucial for solar power battery storage) was already underway in the area.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Following the required environmental review and agency consultation, the federal government issued a permit in October 2024 that authorized the lithium mining project to move forward.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 2023, the largest and fiercest member of the weasel family, the wolverine, was listed as threatened for habitat outside of Alaska.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The listing was controversial because climate change was invoked as a primary cause of the "rising temperatures and declining snowpack" making successful snow cave denning difficult for the remaining populations in the Cascade Range and Rocky Mountains.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The 2023 listing followed a decade of contentious proceedings, starting with the Fish and Wildlife Service itself proposing in 2013 that the wolverine be listed as threatened, then withdrawing its listing proposal the following year.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This prompted a successful district court challenge in Montana by Defenders of Wildlife, based on the agency having "unlawfully ignored the best available science" regarding the impacts of climate change on declining snowpack.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] On remand, the agency in 2018 once again decided a listing was "unwarranted," and again conservation groups sued in court.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] As of early 2025, the 2023 official listing as "threatened" has not been challenged.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 2024, climate change was again stated as cause for a listing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Listing was initially petitioned in 2010 by the Center for Biological Diversity.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] As amended, the Act entails 18 sections.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The substantive policy sections are summarized below.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Section 4 of the ESA sets forth the process by which species are designated as endangered or threatened.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Species with these designations receive protections under federal law.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Section 4 also requires critical habitat designation and recovery plans for those species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Potential candidate species are then prioritized, with "emergency listing" given the highest priority.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Species that face a "significant risk to their well being" are in this category.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The United States Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS) or NOAA Fisheries (also called the National Marine Fisheries Service) can directly list a species through its candidate assessment program, or an individual or organizational petition may request that the FWS or NMFS list a species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] A "species" under the act can be a true taxonomic species, a subspecies, or in the case of vertebrates, a "distinct population segment." The procedures are the same for both types except with the person/organization petition, there is a 90-day screening period.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] During the listing process, economic factors cannot be considered but must be " based solely on the best scientific and commercial data available." The 1982 amendment to the ESA added the word "solely" to prevent any consideration other than the biological status of the species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Congress rejected President Ronald Reagan's Executive Order 12291 which required economic analysis of all government agency actions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The very opposite result happened with the 1978 amendment where Congress added the words "...taking into consideration the economic impact..." in the provision on critical habitat designation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The 1978 amendment linked the listing procedure with critical habitat designation and economic considerations, which almost completely halted new listings, with almost 2,000 species being withdrawn from consideration.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Essentially the "warranted but precluded" finding is a deferral added by the 1982 amendment to the ESA.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] It means other, higher-priority actions will take precedence.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] For example, an emergency listing of a rare plant growing in a wetland that is scheduled to be filled in for housing construction would be a "higher-priority".
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Within another year, a final determination (a final rule) must be made on whether to list the species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The final rule time limit may be extended for 6 months and listings may be grouped together according to similar geography, threats, habitat or taxonomy.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The annual rate of listing (i.e., classifying species as "threatened" or "endangered") increased steadily from the Ford administration (47 listings, 15 per year) through Carter (126 listings, 32 per year), Reagan (255 listings, 32 per year), George H.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Bush (231 listings, 58 per year), and Clinton (521 listings, 65 per year) before decline to its lowest rate under George W.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The rate of listing is strongly correlated with citizen involvement and mandatory timelines: as agency discretion decreases and citizen involvement increases (i.e. filing of petitions and lawsuits) the rate of listing increases.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Citizen involvement has been shown to identify species not moving through the process efficiently, and identify more imperiled species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The longer species are listed, the more likely they are to be classified as recovering by the FWS.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Public notice is given through legal notices in newspapers and communicated to state and county agencies within the species' area.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Foreign nations may also receive notice of a listing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] A public hearing is mandatory if any person has requested one within 45 days of the published notice.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] "The purpose of the notice and comment requirement is to provide for meaningful public participation in the rulemaking process." summarized the Ninth Circuit court in the case of *Idaho Farm Bureau Federation v.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] A frequent basis for ESA litigation is the government's failure to adhere to the law's deadlines for action on petitions to list or delist species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] A 2017 GAO found that, in the preceding decade, nearly 150 lawsuits were filed contesting the government's violation of various ESA deadlines.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The study noted that most of these lawsuits were settled.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Listing status and its abbreviations used in Federal Register and by federal agencies like the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The ESA does allow FWS and NMFS to forgo a recovery plan by declaring it will not benefit the species, but this provision has rarely been invoked.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] It was most famously used to deny a recovery plan to the northern spotted owl in 1991, but in 2006 the FWS changed course and announced it would complete a plan for the species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The ESA does not specify when a recovery plan must be completed.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The FWS has a policy specifying completion within three years of the species being listed, but the average time to completion is approximately six years.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The annual rate of recovery plan completion increased steadily from the Ford administration (4) through Carter (9), Reagan (30), Bush I (44), and Clinton (72), but declined under Bush II (16 per year as of 9/1/06).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The goal of the law is to make itself unnecessary, and recovery plans are a means toward that goal.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Recovery plans became more specific after 1988 when Congress added provisions to Section 4(f) of the law that spelled out the minimum contents of a recovery plan.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The amendment also added public participation to the process.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] There is a ranking order, similar to the listing procedures, for recovery plans, with the highest priority being for species most likely to benefit from recovery plans, especially when the threat is from construction, or other developmental or economic activity.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Recovery plans cover domestic and migratory species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Beginning in 2016, the FWS augmented standard recovery planning by shifting to a three-part framework.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Statutory and regulatory requirements for producing an initial "recovery plan" will still be fulfilled, including opportunities for public comments.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] However, two new kinds of working documents are now developed, posted, and updated as needed for each listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The first updatable document is a "Species Status Assessment" (SSA).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] This, in turn, may stimulate changes in the third part of the new framework: the "Recovery Implementation Strategy" (RIS).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] "Downlisting" of a species can take place when important threats have been controlled and the population in the wild meets recovery objectives.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] To "delist" a species, several factors are considered: control or elimination of threats, population size and growth in the wild, and the stability of habitat quality and quantity.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Species can also be delisted if an error (notably, population size) is found in the data used for listing in the first place.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] More than a dozen species have been delisted under such circumstances.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Three examples of animal species delisted are: the Virginia northern flying squirrel (subspecies) in August 2008, which had been listed since 1985, and the gray wolf (Northern Rocky Mountain DPS), and the bald eagle, which was delisted in 2007 as a result of litigation (*Contoski v.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Scarlett*) brought by a Minnesota landowner objecting to eagle protection rules that prohibited the development of his property.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] On April 15, 2011, President Obama signed the Department of Defense and Full-Year Appropriations Act of 2011.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Section 6 of the Endangered Species Act provided funding for development of programs for management of threatened and endangered species by state wildlife agencies.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Subsequently, lists of endangered and threatened species within their boundaries have been prepared by each state.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] These state lists often include species which are considered endangered or threatened within a specific state but not within all states, and which therefore are not included on the national list of endangered and threatened species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Examples include Florida, Minnesota, and Maine.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Section 7 of the Endangered Species Act requires cooperation among federal agencies to conserve endangered or threatened species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Section 7(a)(1) directs the Secretary of the Interior and all federal agencies to proactively use their authorities to conserve such species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] This directive is often referred to as an 'affirmative requirement.' Section 7(a)(2) of the Act requires federal agencies to ensure their actions do not jeopardize listed species or adversely modify critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Federal agencies (referred to as "action agencies") must consult with the Secretary of the Interior before taking any action which may affect listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Section 7(a)(2) is often referred to as the consultation process.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The two agencies that administer the Act are the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS) and the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] These two agencies are often collectively referred to as "the Services" and lead the consultation process.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] FWS is responsible for the recovery of terrestrial, freshwater, and catadromous species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] NMFS is responsible for marine species and anadromous fish.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] NMFS manages recovery for 165 endangered and threatened marine species including 66 foreign species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] As of January 2020, the Services have listed 2,273 species worldwide as endangered or threatened.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] 1,662 of these species occur in the United States.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Section 7(a)(1) requires federal agencies to work with FWS and NMFS to coordinate endangered and threatened species conservation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Federal agencies should also account for any effects on endangered or threatened species in planning their activities.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] An example of the 7(a)(1) process is the Army Corps of Engineers' management of the Lower Mississippi River.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Since the early 2000s, a division of the U.S.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Army Corps of Engineers has worked with FWS and the states to resolve endangered species and ecosystem management issues.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] ESA-listed species in the area include the least tern (*Sterna antillarum*), pallid sturgeon (*Scaphirhynchus albus*), and the fat pocketbook (*potamilus capax*).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The goal of this 7(a)(1) conservation plan is to protect listed species while allowing the Corps to carry out its civil works responsibilities.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] As part of the plan, the Corps undertakes projects that will benefit those species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] It also considers species ecology as a part of project design.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] All three listed species in the Lower Mississippi River have increased in numbers since the plan was established.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] An action agency is required to consult with the Services if it has reason to believe that a species listed under the ESA may be present in the proposed project area.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] It also must consult if the agency believes the action will likely affect the species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] This requirement, established by section 7(a)(2), is commonly referred to as the consultation process.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Consultation typically begins informally at the request of an action agency in the early stages of project planning.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Discussion topics include listed species in the proposed action area and any effect(s) the action may have on those species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] If both agencies agree that the proposed action is not likely to affect the species, the project moves forward.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] However, if the agency's action may affect a listed species, the agency is required to prepare a biological assessment.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] A biological assessment is a document prepared by the action agency.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] It lays out the project's potential effects, particularly on listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The action agency must complete a biological assessment if listed species or critical habitat may be present.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The assessment is optional if only proposed species or critical habitat are present.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] As a part of the assessment, the action agency conducts on-site inspections to see whether protected species are present.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The assessment will also include the likely effects of the action on such species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The assessment should address all listed and proposed species in the action area, not only those likely to be affected.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The biological assessment may also include conservation measures.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Conservation measures are actions the agency intends to take to promote the recovery of listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] These actions may also serve to minimize the projects' effects on species in the project area.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] There are three possible conclusions to a biological assessment: "no effect", "not likely to adversely affect", or "likely to adversely affect" listed or proposed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The action agency may reach a "no effect" conclusion if it determines the proposed action will not affect listed species or designated critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The action agency may reach a "not likely to adversely affect" decision if the proposed action is insignificant or beneficial.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The Services will then review the biological assessment and either agree or disagree with the agency's findings.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] If the Services agree the project's potential impacts have been eliminated, they will concur in writing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The concurrence letter must outline any modifications agreed to during informal consultation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] If an agreement cannot be reached, the Services advise the action agency to initiate formal consultation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] If the Services or the action agency finds the action "likely to adversely affect" protected species, this triggers formal consultation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] During formal consultation, the Services establish the project's effects on listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Specifically, they address whether the project will jeopardize the continued existence of any listed species or destroy/adversely modify species' designated critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] To assess the likelihood of jeopardy, the Services will review the species' biological and ecological traits.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] These could include the species' population dynamics (population size, variability and stability), life-history traits, critical habitat, and how any proposed action might alter its critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] They also consider how limited the species' range is and whether the threats that led to species listing have improved or worsened since listing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The Services have defined adverse modification as "a diminishment of critical habitat that leads to a lower likelihood of survival and recovery for a listed species." The diminishment may be direct or indirect.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] To assess the likelihood of adverse modification, biologists will first verify the scope of the proposed action.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] This includes identifying the area likely to be affected and considering the proximity of the action to species or designated critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The duration and frequency of any disturbance to the species or its habitat is also assessed.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] A formal consultation may last up to 90 days.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] After this time the Services will issue a biological opinion.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The biological opinion contains findings related to the project's effects on listed and proposed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The Services must complete the biological opinion within 45 days of the conclusion of formal consultation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] However, the Services may extend this timeline if they require more information to make a determination.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The action agency must agree to the extension.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The Services may issue a finding of "no jeopardy or adverse modification" if the proposed action does not pose any harm to listed or proposed species or their designated critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Alternatively, the Service could find that proposed action is likely to harm listed or proposed species or their critical habitat but does not reach the level of jeopardy or adverse modification.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] In this case, the Services will prepare an incidental take statement.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Under most circumstances, the ESA prohibits "take" of listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Take includes harming, killing or harassing a listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] However, the ESA allows for "incidental" take that results from an otherwise lawful activity that is not the direct purpose of the action.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] An incidental take statement will be agreed to between the Services and the action agency.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The statement should describe the amount of anticipated take due to the proposed action.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] It will also include "reasonable and prudent measures" to minimize the take.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Incidental take cannot pose jeopardy or potential extinction to species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Following formal consultation, the Services may determine that the action will result in jeopardy or adverse modification to critical habitat.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] If this is the case, this finding will be included in the biological opinion.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] However, during consultation, the Services may find there are actions that the agency may take to avoid this.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] These actions are known as reasonable and prudent alternative actions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] In the event of a jeopardy or adverse modification finding, the agency must adopt reasonable and prudent alternative actions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] However, the Services retain final say on which are included in the biological opinion.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The action agency must notify the Services of its course of action on any project that receives a jeopardy or adverse modification opinion.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] In the past ten years, FWS has made jeopardy determinations in three cases (delta smelt, aquatic species in Idaho, and South Florida water management), each of which has included reasonable and prudent alternatives.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] No project has been stopped as a result of FWS finding a project had no available path forward.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] This fact however, does not present the full picture, as even where projects can proceed, Section 7 consultation regularly results in dramatic and costly changes to the scope of such projects.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] And in practice, the result of consultation under the ESA is almost always the imposition of additional restrictions on land use activity.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] In rare cases, no alternatives to avoid jeopardy or adverse modification will be available.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] An analysis of FWS consultations from 1987 to 1991 found only 0.02% were blocked or canceled because of a jeopardy or adverse modification opinion with no reasonable and prudent alternatives.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] In this scenario, the only option that the action agency and applicant are left with is to apply for an exemption.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Exemptions are decided upon by the Endangered Species Committee.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] An action agency may apply for an exemption if: (1) it believes it cannot comply with the requirements of the biological opinion; or (2) formal consultation yields no reasonable and prudent alternative actions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The exemption application must be submitted to the Secretary of the Interior within 90 days of the conclusion of formal consultation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The Secretary can then recommend the application to the Endangered Species Committee (informally known as "The God Squad").
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The governor of each affected state is notified of any exemption applications.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The governor will recommend a representative to join the committee for this application decision.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Once this information is received, the committee and the secretary will hold a public hearing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The committee has 30 days from the time of receiving the above report to make a decision.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] In order for the exemption to be granted, five out of the seven members must vote in favor of the exemption.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The findings can be challenged in federal court.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] In 1992, one such challenge was the case of*Portland Audubon Society* v.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] *Endangered Species Committee* heard in the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The court found that three members had been in illegal *ex parte* contact with the then-President George H.W.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Bush, a violation of the Administrative Procedure Act.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The committee's exemption was for the Bureau of Land Management's timber sale and "incidental takes" of the endangered northern spotted owl in Oregon.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Rarely does the Endangered Species Committee consider projects for exemption.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The Endangered Species Committee has only met four times since the inception of the ESA.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] An exemption was granted on three of these occasions.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Most recently, in March 2026, the committee voted unanimously to exempt the oil and gas industry in the Gulf of Mexico from all endangered species regulations, upon the recommendation of Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The Center for Biological Diversity is challenging the exemption before the United States District Court for the District of Columbia.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The exemption is expected to drive the Rice's whale to extinction.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Section 10 of the ESA provides a permit system that may allow acts prohibited by Section 9.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] This includes scientific and conservation activities.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] For example, the government may let someone move a species from one area to another.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] This would otherwise be a prohibited taking under Section 9.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Before the law was amended in 1982, a listed species could be taken only for scientific or research purposes.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The combined result of the amendments to the Endangered Species Act have created a more flexible ESA.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] More changes were made in the 1990s in an attempt by Secretary of the Interior Bruce Babbitt to shield the ESA from a Congress hostile to the law.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] He instituted incentive-based strategies that would balance the goals of economic development and conservation.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Section 10 may also allow activities that can unintentionally impact protected species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] A common activity might be construction where these species live.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] More than half of habitat for listed species is on non-federal property.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Under section 10, impacted parties can apply for an incidental take permit (ITP).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] An application for an ITP requires a Habitat Conservation Plan (HCP).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] HCPs must minimize and mitigate the impacts of the activity.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] HCPs can be established to provide protections for both listed and non-listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Such non-listed species include species that have been proposed for listing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] However, the effectiveness of the HCP program remains unknown.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] If activities may unintentionally take a protected species, an incidental take permit can be issued.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The applicant submits an application with an habitat conservation plan (HCP).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] If approved by the agency (FWS or NMFS) they are issued an Incidental Take Permit (ITP).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The permit allows a certain number of the species to be "taken." The Services have a "No Surprises" policy for HCPs.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Once an ITP is granted, the Services cannot require applicants to spend more money or set aside additional land or pay more.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] To receive the benefit of the permit the applicant must comply with all the requirements of the HCP.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Because the permit is issued by a federal agency to a private party, it is a federal action.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Other federal laws will apply such as the National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA) and Administrative Procedure Act (APA).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] A notice of the permit application action must be published in the *Federal Register* and a public comment period of 30 to 90 days offered.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The "Safe Harbor" agreement (SHA) is similar to an HCP.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] It is voluntary between the private landowner and the Services.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The landowner agrees to alter the property to benefit a listed or proposed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] In exchange, the Services will allow some future "takes" through an Enhancement of Survival Permit.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] A landowner can have either a "Safe Harbor" agreement or an HCP, or both.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The policy was developed by the Clinton administration.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Unlike an HCP the activities covered by a SHA are designed to protect species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The policy relies on the "enhancement of survival" provision of Section §1539(a)(1)(A).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Safe harbor agreements are subject to public comment rules of the APA.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] HCPs and SHAs are applied to listed species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] If an activity may "take" a proposed or candidate species, parties can enter into Candidate Conservation Agreements With Assurances (CCAA).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] A party must show the Services they will take conservation measures to prevent listing.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] If a CCAA is approved and the species is later listed, the party with a CCAA gets an automatic "enhancement of survival" permit under Section §1539(a)(1)(A).
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] CCAAs are subject to the public comment rules of the APA.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Experimental populations are listed species that have been intentionally introduced to a new area.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] They must be separate geographically from other populations of the same species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Experimental populations can be designated "essential" or "non-essential" "Essential" populations are those whose loss would appreciably reduce the survival of the species in the wild.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] "Non-essential" populations are all others.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Nonessential experimental populations of listed species typically receive less protection than populations in the wild.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] There are different degrees of violation with the law.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The most punishable offenses are trafficking, and any act of knowingly "taking" (which includes harming, wounding, or killing) an endangered species.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The penalties for these violations can be a maximum fine of up to $50,000 or imprisonment for one year, or both, and civil penalties of up to $25,000 per violation may be assessed.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Lists of violations and exact fines are available through the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration website.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] These penalties are subject to the Federal Civil Penalties Inflation Adjustment Act Improvements Act of 2015, and as of 2024 had increased to $63,991 for knowing violations of the ESA's take prohibition, and $30,715 for any other knowing violation of the ESA.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] One provision of this law is that no penalty may be imposed if, by a preponderance of the evidence that the act was in self-defense.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The law also eliminates criminal penalties for accidentally killing listed species during farming and ranching activities.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] In addition to fines or imprisonment, a license, permit, or other agreement issued by a federal agency that authorized an individual to import or export fish, wildlife, or plants may be revoked, suspended or modified.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] Any federal hunting or fishing permits that were issued to a person who violates the ESA can be canceled or suspended for up to a year.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] A reward will be paid to any person who furnishes information which leads to an arrest, conviction, or revocation of a license, so long as they are not a local, state, or federal employee in the performance of official duties.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] The Secretary may *also* provide reasonable and necessary costs incurred for the care of fish, wildlife, and forest service or plant pending the violation caused by the criminal.
[src:committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p05] If the balance ever exceeds $500,000 the Secretary of the Treasury is required to deposit an amount equal to the excess into the cooperative endangered species conservation fund.
